perience. I tried and failed (and eventually succeeded) over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you, too, don\'t feel horrendously useless. If in reality you actually *are* horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So walk beside me on this mystical journey, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Ground Rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i>. The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Archlinux</li>\r\n  <li>RVM</li>\r\n  <li>nginx</li>\r\n  <li>Passenger</li>\r\n  <li>fast-cgi</li>\r\n  <li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li>\r\n  <li>Rails</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, soldier.</p>\r\n\r\n','Basic Server Management<br /> (for hackers)','','publish','open','closed','','basic-server-management-for-hackers','','','2011-05-06 06:25:48','2011-05-06 06:25:48','',2,'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=22',0,'page','',0),(23,1,'2011-03-31 04:48:30','2011-03-31 04:48:30','','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision','','','2011-03-31 04:48:30','2011-03-31 04:48:30','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/23/22-revision',0,'revision','',0),(24,1,'2011-03-31 04:46:39','2011-03-31 04:46:39','There be articles here at some point','Articles','','inherit','open','open','','2-revision-2','','','2011-03-31 04:46:39','2011-03-31 04:46:39','',2,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/24/2-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(25,1,'2011-04-29 07:19:55','2011-04-29 07:19:55','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivia, but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed (and eventually succeeded) over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you, too, don\'t feel horrendously useless. If in reality you actually *are* horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So walk beside me on this mystical journey, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\n<h1>Ground Rules</h1>\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i>. The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\n<ul>\n  <li>Archlinux</li>\n  <li>RVM</li>\n  <li>nginx</li>\n  <li>Passenger</li>\n  <li>fast-cgi</li>\n  <li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li>\n  <li>Rails</li>\n</ul>\n\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, soldier.</p>\n\n','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-autosave','','','2011-04-29 07:19:55','2011-04-29 07:19:55','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/25/22-autosave',0,'revision','',0),(26,1,'2011-03-31 04:48:39','2011-03-31 04:48:39','This is textity text-text.','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-2','','','2011-03-31 04:48:39','2011-03-31 04:48:39','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/26/22-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(27,1,'2011-04-03 04:56:40','2011-04-03 04:56:40','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivial - but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you too don\'t feel horrendously useless. If, in reality, you <i>are</i> horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So come along, my homies, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-3','','','2011-04-03 04:56:40','2011-04-03 04:56:40','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/27/22-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(28,1,'2011-04-03 05:00:45','2011-04-03 05:00:45','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivial - but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you too don\'t feel horrendously useless. If, in reality, you <i>are</i> horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So come along, my homies, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Yo, here be ground rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i> (that is, a collection of technologies that will comprise our server). The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul><li>Archlinux</li><li>nginx</li><li>Passenger</li><li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li><li>RVM</li><li>Rails</li></ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, private.</p>','Basic Server Management (for hac