 a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you too don\'t feel horrendously useless. If, in reality, you <i>are</i> horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So come along, my homies, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Yo, here be ground rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i> (that is, a collection of technologies that will comprise our server). The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul><li>Archlinux</li><li>nginx</li><li>Passenger</li><li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li><li>RVM</li><li>Rails</li></ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, private.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Archlinus, that friend you have that doesn\'t own much</h1>','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-6','','','2011-04-03 05:04:53','2011-04-03 05:04:53','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/30/22-revision-6',0,'revision','',0),(31,1,'2011-04-03 05:04:59','2011-04-03 05:04:59','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivial - but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you too don\'t feel horrendously useless. If, in reality, you <i>are</i> horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So come along, my homies, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Yo, here be ground rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i> (that is, a collection of technologies that will comprise our server). The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul><li>Archlinux</li><li>nginx</li><li>Passenger</li><li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li><li>RVM</li><li>Rails</li></ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, private.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Archlinux, that friend you have that doesn\'t own much</h1>','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-7','','','2011-04-03 05:04:59','2011-04-03 05:04:59','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/31/22-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(32,1,'2011-04-03 05:12:31','2011-04-03 05:12:31','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivial - but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you too don\'t feel horrendously useless. If, in reality, you <i>are</i> horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So come along, my homies, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Yo, here be ground rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i> (that is, a collection of technologies that will comprise our server). The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul><li>Archlinux</li><li>nginx</li><li>Passenger</li><li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li><li>RVM</li><li>Rails</li></ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, private.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Archlinux, that friend you have that doesn\'t own much</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux is a distribution (\"distro\") of Linux that is, to be blunt, hella minimalistic. I\'m not going to tell you how to install it, because there\'s <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">already good guidance here</a>. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care. At this point in time, we perform one important operation:<p>\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-8','','','2011-04-03 05:12:31','2011-04-03 05:12:31','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/32/22-revision-8',0,'revision','',0),(33,1,'2011-04-03 05:13:48','2011-04-03 05:13:48','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivial - but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you too don\'t feel horrendously useless. If, in reality, you <i>are</i> horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So come along, my homies, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Yo, here be ground rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i> (that is, a collection of technologies that will comprise our server). The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul><li>Archlinux</li><li>nginx</li><li>Passenger</li><li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li><li>RVM</li><li>Rails</li></ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, private.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Archlinux, that friend you have that doesn\'t own much</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux is a distribution (\"distro\") of Linux that is, to be blunt, hella minimalistic. I\'m not going to tell you how to install it, because there\'s <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">already good guidance here</a>. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-9','','','2011-04-03 05:13:48','2011-04-03 05:13:48','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/33/22-revision-9',0,'revision','',0),(34,1,'2011-04-03 05:14:16','2011-04-03 05:14:16','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivial - but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you too don\'t feel horrendously useless. If, in reality, you <i>are</i> horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So come along, my homies, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Yo, here be ground rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i> (that is, a collection of technologies that will comprise our server). The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul><li>Archlinux</li><li>nginx</li><li>Passenger</li><li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li><li>RVM</li><li>Rails</li></ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, private.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Archlinux, that friend you have that doesn\'t own much</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux is a distribution (\"distro\") of Linux that is, to be blunt, hella minimalistic. I\'m not going to tell you how to install it, because there\'s <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">already good guidance here</a>. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<p>We begin with this:\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\n</p>','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-10','','','2011-04-03 05:14:16','2011-04-03 05:14:16','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/34/22-revision-10',0,'revision','',0),(35,1,'2011-04-03 05:18:12','2011-04-03 05:18:12','<p class=\"overview\">\"Archlinux behooves one to reclaim what the gentry once discarded as commonplace\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux is a very minimalistic distribution. There is beauty in simplicity. There\'s also less things to go wrong. Think of it as a blank canvas. If we were trying to paint something beautiful on a already-used canvas, we would either have to respect previous elements of said work, or \"reset\" the canvas with paint-stripper or something. I think the analogy is breaking down - much like paint.</p>\r\n<h1>Installation</h1>\r\n<p>There are <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">installation instructions </a> already written. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Pacman (waka waka waka)</h1>\r\n<p>At your prompt, type:\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t Pacman a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nNo.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora (amongst others) will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means when we\'re ready, we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install, rather than outdated versions. It also means pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p><p>\r\n<h1>Watching Me, Watching You</h1>\r\n<p>Now is a <i>very</i> good time to change your mirror. Archlinux\'s mirrorlist is located at <tt>/etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist</tt>. It defaults to a USA server; you may live outside the USA. Find the server listed that is the best fit, and remove the hashes from the front. You can put hashes in front of the USA server if you so choose. Right up the top is a mirrorlist that is as official as you can get (i.e., all current packages will be there - avoiding delays in replication across the other mirrors). It\'s your choice. I went with one in Australia, because that is where I live. Also, it\'s pretty up to date.</p>\r\n<p>After you\'ve done this, resync the databases, and update the system:\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nIf you\'re asked to upgrade the database by running a script, run said script. Then <tt>pacman -Syu</tt> again. For safety\'s sake. At this point, you have a system that\'s good to go.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Hooray!</h1>\r\n<p>This is... pretty much all we need to do to our general Archlinux setup before we begin installing things. Yeah, I was really expecting this page to be longer, too.</p>\r\n','archlinux','','publish','open','open','','archlinux','','','2011-04-21 07:20:12','2011-04-21 07:20:12','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=35',0,'page','',0),(36,1,'2011-04-03 05:17:44','2011-04-03 05:17:44','','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision','','','2011-04-03 05:17:44','2011-04-03 05:17:44','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/36/35-revision',0,'revision','',0),(37,1,'2011-04-03 05:18:12','2011-04-03 05:18:12','YAY','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-2','','','2011-04-03 05:18:12','2011-04-03 05:18:12','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/37/35-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(38,1,'2011-04-03 05:16:26','2011-04-03 05:16:26','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for 