view\">Archlinux is a distribution of Linux that is, to be blunt, hella minimalistic. I\'m not going to tell you how to install it, because there\'s <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">already good guidance here</a>. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Waka waka waka (a.k.a: pacman)</h1>\r\n<p>We begin with the following:\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t \"pacman\" a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nCalm down.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install. It also means our pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p>','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-9','','','2011-04-03 13:42:25','2011-04-03 13:42:25','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/46/35-revision-9',0,'revision','',0),(47,1,'2011-04-03 13:44:51','2011-04-03 13:44:51','<p class=\"overview\">Archlinux is a distribution of Linux that is, to be blunt, hella minimalistic. There are <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">installation instructions </a> already written. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Pacman (waka waka waka)</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t \"pacman\" a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nCalm down.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install. It also means our pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p><p>\r\nThis is... pretty much all we need to do to our general Archlinux setup before we begin installing things. Yeah, I was really expecting this page to be longer, too.</p>','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-10','','','2011-04-03 13:44:51','2011-04-03 13:44:51','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/47/35-revision-10',0,'revision','',0),(48,1,'2011-04-03 14:04:39','2011-04-03 14:04:39','<p class=\"overview\">\"To serve one\'s country - that is the dream. That, and occasionally a very naughty nurse\" - Voltaire</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Install Passenger</h1>\r\n<p>\"nginx with Passenger support\" doesn\'t mean that Passenger is installed. Installation is very easy, however:\r\n<pre>gem install passenger</pre>\r\nYes, it\'s just a ruby gem. And we\'re done. We are literally done. Move on.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\r\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\r\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\r\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\r\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). </p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Final Configuration (important)</h1>\r\n<p>We\'re not finished just yet. We will need to tell nginx where to find the Passenger executables and what-not. nginx\'s configuration is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. It\'s a file - open it with whatever text-editor you like (this author sheepishly admits to using nano, having never used a terminal for any significant editing). You\'ll see a whole bunch of stuff in there. Go take a look, look at the nginx documentation if you want to know what some of it does, we\'ll definitely be coming back to it later. We\'re going to add two lines. One will tell nginx where Passenger has its <i>things</i>, the other line will tell nginx where to find a ruby executable for Passenger to use.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s figure out where our passenger root is:\r\n<pre>passenger-config --root</pre>\r\nBam! <tt>passenger-config</tt> should display a path to where Passenger is installed to. Remember this! We shall call it <tt>output #1</tt>. We\'re also going to need to know where our ruby is:\r\n<pre>which ruby</pre>\r\nHooray! We shall call this <tt>output #2</tt>. Now we have the information we need to configure nginx. Look at the following:\r\n<pre>passenger_root [output #1]\r\npassenger_ruby [output #2]</pre>\r\nDon\'t include those square brackets. Mine looks like this:\r\n<pre>\r\npassenger_root /usr/local/rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p180/gems/passenger-3.0.6\r\npassenger_ruby /usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby\r\n</pre>\r\nNow, finally, place those two lines into your <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt> file. Somewhere near the top - outside the <tt>html</tt> block (some would say the <i>top-level</i>). Awesome. Quick! Reload the nginx configuration:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</pre>\r\nAnd breathe.\r\n<h1>Summary</h1>\r\nYou now have nginx with Passenger up and running. You still don\'t have Rails installed, and you have nothing to point your webserver to. We will rectify this shortly.','nginx & Friends','','publish','open','open','','nginx','','','2011-05-02 08:05:05','2011-05-02 08:05:05','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=48',2,'page','',0),(49,1,'2011-04-03 14:04:25','2011-04-03 14:04:25','','nginx','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision','','','2011-04-03 14:04:25','2011-04-03 14:04:25','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/49/48-revision',0,'revision','',0),(50,1,'2011-05-02 08:04:14','2011-05-02 08:04:14','<p class=\"overview\">\"To serve one\'s country - that is the dream. That, and occasionally a very naughty nurse\" - Voltaire</p>\n\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\n\n<h1>Install Passenger</h1>\n<p>\"nginx with Passenger support\" doesn\'t mean that Passenger is installed.\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\ncd nginx-passenger\n</pre>\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\n</p>\n\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\n<p>\nLet\'s just do it:\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\n</p>\n\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). </p>\n\n<h1>Final Configuration (important)</h1>\n<p>We\'re not finished just yet. We will need to tell nginx where to find the Passenger executables and what-not. nginx\'s configuration is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. It\'s a file - open it with whatever text-editor you like (this author sheepishly admits to using nano, having never used a terminal for any significant editing). You\'ll see a whole bunch of stuff in there. Go take a look, look at the nginx documentation if you want to know what some of it does, we\'ll definitely be coming back to it later. We\'re going to add two lines. One will tell nginx where Passenger has its <i>things</i>, the other line will tell nginx where to find a ruby executable for Passenger to use.</p>\n<p>Let\'s figure out where our passenger root is:\n<pre>passenger-config --root</pre>\nBam! <tt>passenger-config</tt> should display a path to where Passenger is installed to. Remember this! We shall call it <tt>output #1</tt>. We\'re also going to need to know where our ruby is:\n<pre>which ruby</pre>\nHooray! We shall call this <tt>output #2</tt>. Now we have the information we need to configure nginx. Look at the following:\n<pre>passenger_root [output #1]\npassenger_ruby [output #2]</pre>\nDon\'t include those square brackets. Mine looks like this:\n<pre>\npassenger_root /usr/local/rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p180/gems/passenger-3.0.6\npassenger_ruby /usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby\n</pre>\nNow, finally, place those two lines into your <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt> file. Somewhere near the top - outside the <tt>html</tt> block (some would say the <i>top-level</i>). Awesome. Quick! Reload the nginx configuration:\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</pre>\nAnd breathe.\n<h1>Summary</h1>\nYou now have nginx with Passenger up and running. You still don\'t have Rails installed, and you have nothing to point your webserver to. We will rectify this shortly.','nginx & Friends','','inherit','open','open','','48-autosave','','','2011-05-02 08:04:14','2011-05-02 08:04:14','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/50/48-autosave',0,'revision','',0),(51,1,'2011-04-03 14:04:39','2011-04-03 14:04:39','nginx is a tricky little guy','nginx','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-2','','','2011-04-03 14:04:39','2011-04-03 14:04:39','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/51/48-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(53,1,'2011-04-03 13:47:05','2011-04-03 13:47:05','<p class=\"overview\">Archlinux is a distribution of Linux that is, to be blunt, hella minimalistic. There are <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">installation instructions </a> already written. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Pacman (waka waka waka)</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t Pacman a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nCalm down.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora (amongst others) will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means when we\'re ready, we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install, rather than outdated versions. It also means pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p><p>\r\nThis is... pretty much all we need to do to our general Archlinux setup before we begin installing things. Yeah, I was really expecting this page to be longer, too.</p>','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-11','','','2011-04-03 13:47:05','2011-04-03 13:47:05','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/53/35-revision-11',0,'revision','',0),(54,1,'2011-04-03 06:22:57','2011-04-03 06:22:57','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\r\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>OnLoad</h1>\r\n<p>When we login, we\'ll need to initialise RVM, with the following line placed in one of our <a href=\"appendix-a-startup-files\">startup files</a>:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nMake sure you\'ve read the appendix on startup-files! You\'ll probably want to place the line in <tt>.bashsrc</tt>, and source <tt>.bashrc</tt> from <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, like most configurations. <i>Remember</i>: We need to place the line in both <tt>/root/</tt> and <tt>/etc/skel/</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby - indeed, they will compile the vast majority of packages we install. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','publish','open','open','','rvm-ruby','','','2011-05-06 06:27:20','2011-05-06 06:27:20','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=54',1,'page','',0),(55,1,'2011-04-04 06:22:10','2011-04-04 06:22:10','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only \n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision','','','2011-04-04 06:22:10','2011-04-04 06:22:10','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/55/54-revision',0,'revision','',0),(56,1,'2011-04-04 06:22:57','2011-04-04 06:22:57','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-2','','','2011-04-04 06:22:57','2011-04-04 06:22:57','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/56/54-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(57,1,'2011-04-19 06:29:36','2011-04-19 06:29:36','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. So... let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\n</p>\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\n\n<h1>OnLoad</h1>\n<p>When we login, we\'ll need to initialise RVM, with the following line placed in one of our <a href=\"appendix-a-startup-files\">startup files</a>:\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\nMake sure you\'ve read the appendix on startup-files! You\'ll probably want to place the line in <tt>.bashsrc</tt>, and source <tt>.bashrc</tt> from <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, like most configurations. <i>Remember</i>: We need to place the line in both <tt>/root/</tt> and <tt>/etc/skel/</tt>.</p>\n\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\n\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby - indeed, they will compile the vast majority of packages we install. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-autosave','','','2011-04-19 06:29:36','2011-04-19 06:29:36','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/57/54-autosave',0,'revision','',0),(58,1,'2011-04-04 06:23:05','2011-04-04 06:23:05','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-3','','','2011-04-04 06:23:05','2011-04-04 06:23:05','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/58/54-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(59,1,'2011-04-04 06:34:05','2011-04-04 06:34:05','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-4','','','2011-04-04 06:34:05','2011-04-04 06:34:05','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/59/54-revision-4',0,'revision','',0),(60,1,'2011-04-04 06:43:58','2011-04-04 06:43:58','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"<pre>\r\n\r\nThat tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bashrc</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bashrc</tt> file too. ','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-5','','','2011-04-04 06:43:58','2011-04-04 06:43:58','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/60/54-revision-5',0,'revision','',0),(61,1,'2011-04-04 06:44:59','2011-04-04 06:44:59','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\n\r\nThat tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bashrc</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bashrc</tt> file too. ','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-6','','','2011-04-04 06:44:59','2011-04-04 06:44:59','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/61/54-revision-6',0,'revision','',0),(62,1,'2011-04-04 06:47:17','2011-04-04 06:47:17','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\n\r\nThat tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bashrc</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bashrc</tt> file too.</p>\r\n<p><b>We need to modify <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt></b>. ','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-7','','','2011-04-04 06:47:17','2011-04-04 06:47:17','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/62/54-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(63,1,'2011-04-04 06:47:41','2011-04-04 06:47:41','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\n\r\nThat tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bashrc</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bashrc</tt> file too.</p>\r\n<p><i>We need to modify <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt></i>. ','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-8','','','2011-04-04 06:47:41','2011-04-04 06:47:41','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/63/54-revision-8',0,'revision','',0),(64,1,'2011-04-04 06:51:48','2011-04-04 06:51:48','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\n\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bashrc</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bashrc</tt> file too.</p>\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in the directory of <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Files under that directory are called \"skeleton files\" - and they\'re used to create new users (including root, I guess). Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bashrc</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-9','','','2011-04-04 06:51:48','2011-04-04 06:51:48','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/64/54-revision-9',0,'revision','',0),(65,1,'2011-04-04 06:53:29','2011-04-04 06:53:29','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\n\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bashrc</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bashrc</tt> file too.</p>\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in the directory of <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Files under that directory are called \"skeleton files\" - and they\'re used to create new users (including root, I guess). Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bashrc</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, to recap: After the installation of RVM, we need to write \"the line\" in two different places: <tt>/root/.bashrc</tt>, and <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>.</p>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-10','','','2011-04-04 06:53:29','2011-04-04 06:53:29','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/65/54-revision-10',0,'revision','',0),(66,1,'2011-04-04 06:54:28','2011-04-04 06:54:28','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas,