o create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>In Summary</h1>\r\n<p>After installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" in two different places: <tt>/root/.bashrc</tt>, and <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt></p>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-11','','','2011-04-04 06:54:28','2011-04-04 06:54:28','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/66/54-revision-11',0,'revision','',0),(67,1,'2011-04-04 13:17:16','2011-04-04 13:17:16','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bashrc</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bashrc</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bashrc</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>In Summary</h1>\r\n<p>After installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt></p>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-12','','','2011-04-04 13:17:16','2011-04-04 13:17:16','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/67/54-revision-12',0,'revision','',0),(68,1,'2011-04-05 04:14:36','2011-04-05 04:14:36','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash shells. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bashrc</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bashrc</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"background: yellow\">\r\n<h1>Aside: <tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>What\'s the difference? What do Linuxes actually <i>do</i> in the start of a terminal session?</p>\r\n</span>\r\n<h1>In Summary</h1>\r\n<p>After installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt></p>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-13','','','2011-04-05 04:14:36','2011-04-05 04:14:36','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/68/54-revision-13',0,'revision','',0),(69,1,'2011-04-05 04:14:54','2011-04-05 04:14:54','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple ver