>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bashrc</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bashrc</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h1>In Summary</h1>\r\n<p>After installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt></p>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-19','','','2011-04-05 06:06:51','2011-04-05 06:06:51','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/74/54-revision-19',0,'revision','',0),(75,1,'2011-04-05 06:50:45','2011-04-05 06:50:45','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h1>In Summary</h1>\r\n<p>After installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-20','','','2011-04-05 06:50:45','2011-04-05 06:50:45','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/75/54-revision-20',0,'revision','',0),(76,1,'2011-04-05 07:01:37','2011-04-05 07:01:37','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-21','','','2011-04-05 07:01:37','2011-04-05 07:01:37','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/76/54-revision-21',0,'revision','',0),(77,1,'2011-04-06 02:26:17','2011-04-06 02:26:17','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<code>pacman -S gcc make</code>\r\nThese packages are required for compiling Ruby. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<code>rvm install 1.9.2</code>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. ','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-22','','','2011-04-06 02:26:17','2011-04-06 02:26:17','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/77/54-revision-22',0,'revision','',0),(78,1,'2011-04-06 02:39:31','2011-04-06 02:39:31','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S gcc make</pre>\r\nThese packages are required for compiling Ruby. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. ','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-23','','','2011-04-06 02:39:31','2011-04-06 02:39:31','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/78/54-revision-23',0,'revision','',0),(79,1,'2011-04-07 04:53:00','2011-04-07 04:53:00','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S gcc make</pre>\r\nThese packages are required for compiling Ruby. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nThe <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-24','','','2011-04-07 04:53:00','2011-04-07 04:53:00','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/79/54-revision-24',0,'revision','',0),(80,1,'2011-04-07 04:55:26','2011-04-07 04:55:26','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S gcc make</pre>\r\nThese packages are required for compiling Ruby. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-25','','','2011-04-07 04:55:26','2011-04-07 04:55:26','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/80/54-revision-25',0,'revision','',0),(81,1,'2011-04-07 05:36:48','2011-04-07 05:36:48','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby, well, almost everything ever, actually. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-26','','','2011-04-07 05:36:48','2011-04-07 05:36:48','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/81/54-revision-26',0,'revision','',0),(82,1,'2011-04-03 15:34:30','2011-04-03 15:34:30','<p class=\"overview\">There\'s an \"easy\" way of doing this, and a \"hard\" way. We\'re hackers, right? We don\'t mind compiling stuff?</p>\r\n<h1>nginx & Passenger: The Easy Way</h1>\r\n<p>The problem is that nginx, unlike Apache, doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! I don\'t know why this is so, but it\'s a barrier to entry that people must overcome. In the easy way, we\'ll overcome it by... not installing nginx. Instead, we\'ll get the','nginx','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-3','','','2011-04-03 15:34:30','2011-04-03 15:34:30','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/82/48-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(83,1,'2011-04-08 03:22:57','2011-04-08 03:22:57','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. The problem with nginx, however, is unlike Apache, it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this reasonably easy for us. In fact, we won\'t even be doing any (manual) compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. ','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-4','','','2011-04-08 03:22:57','2011-04-08 03:22:57','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/83/48-revision-4',0,'revision','',0),(85,1,'2011-04-08 05:39:39','2011-04-08 05:39:39','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-5','','','2011-04-08 05:39:39','2011-04-08 05:39:39','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/85/48-revision-5',0,'revision','',0),(86,1,'2011-04-10 05:51:40','2011-04-10 05:51:40','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n\r\n<h1><tt>makepkg</tt></h1>\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. ','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-6','','','2011-04-10 05:51:40','2011-04-10 05:51:40','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/86/48-revision-6',0,'revision','',0),(87,1,'2011-04-10 05:52:30','2011-04-10 05:52:30','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. ','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-7','','','2011-04-10 05:52:30','2011-04-10 05:52:30','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/87/48-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(88,1,'2011-04-10 05:53:16','2011-04-10 05:53:16','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>~/AUR/nginx-passenger$ makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. ','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-8','','','2011-04-10 05:53:16','2011-04-10 05:53:16','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/88/48-revision-8',0,'revision','',0),(89,1,'2011-04-10 06:02:14','2011-04-10 06:02:14','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\r\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\r\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\r\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\r\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). ','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-9','','','2011-04-10 06:02:14','2011-04-10 06:02:14','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/89/48-revision-9',0,'revision','',0),(90,1,'2011-04-10 15:38:50','2011-04-10 15:38:50','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\r\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\r\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\r\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\r\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). </p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Final Configuration (important)</h1>\r\n<p>We\'re not finished just yet. We will need to tell nginx where to find the Passenger executables and what-not. nginx\'s configuration is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. It\'s a file - open it with whatever text-editor you like (this author sheepishly admits to using nano, having never used a terminal for any significant editing). You\'ll see a whole bunch of stuff in there. Go take a look, look at the nginx documentation if you want to know what some of it does, we\'ll definitely be coming back to it later. We\'re going to add two lines. One will tell nginx where Passenger has its <i>things</i>, the other line will tell nginx where to find a ruby executable for Passenger to use.</p>\r\n\r\n','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-10','','','2011-04-10 15:38:50','2011-04-10 15:38:50','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/90/48-revision-10',0,'revision','',0),(91,1,'2011-04-11 05:51:08','2011-04-11 05:51:08','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\r\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\r\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\r\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\r\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). </p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Final Configuration (important)</h1>\r\n<p>We\'re not finished just yet. We will need to tell nginx where to find the Passenger executables and what-not. nginx\'s configuration is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. It\'s a file - open it with whatever text-editor you like (this author sheepishly admits to using nano, having never used a terminal for any significant editing). You\'ll see a whole bunch of stuff in there. Go take a look, look at the nginx documentation if you want to know what some of it does, we\'ll definitely be coming back to it later. We\'re going to add two lines. One will tell nginx where Passenger has its <i>things</i>, the other line will tell nginx where to find a ruby executable for Passenger to use.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s figure out where our passenger root is:\r\n<pre>passenger-config --root</pre>\r\nBam! <tt>passenger-config</tt> should display a path to where Passenger is installed to. Remember this! We shall call it <tt>output #1</tt>. We\'re also going to need to know where our ruby is:\r\n<pre>which ruby</pre>\r\nHooray! We shall call this <tt>output #2</tt>. Now we have the information we need to configure nginx. Look at the following:\r\n<pre>passenger_root <output #1>\r\npassenger_ruby <output #2></pre>\r\nDon\'t include those triangle brackets. Mine looks like this:\r\n<pre>\r\npassenger_root /usr/local/rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p180/gems/passenger-3.0.6\r\npassenger_ruby /usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-11','','','2011-04-11 05:51:08','2011-04-11 05:51:08','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/91/48-revision-11',0,'revision','',0),(92,1,'2011-04-11 05:51:55','2011-04-11 05:51:55','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\r\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\r\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\r\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\r\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). </p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Final Configuration (important)</h1>\r\n<p>We\'re not finished just yet. We will need to tell nginx where to find the Passenger executables and what-not. nginx\'s configuration is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. It\'s a file - open it with whatever text-editor you like (this author sheepishly admits to using nano, having never used a terminal for any significant editing). You\'ll see a whole bunch of stuff in there. Go take a look, look at the nginx documentation if you want to know what some of it does, we\'ll definitely be coming back to it later. We\'re going to add two lines. One will tell nginx where Passenger has its <i>things</i>, the other line will tell nginx where to find a ruby executable for Passenger to use.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s figure out where our passenger root is:\r\n<pre>passenger-config --root</pre>\r\nBam! <tt>passenger-config</tt> should display a path to where Passenger is installed to. Remember this! We shall call it <tt>output #1</tt>. We\'re also going to need to know where our ruby is:\r\n<pre>which ruby</pre>\r\nHooray! We shall call this <tt>output #2</tt>. Now we have the information we need to configure nginx. Look at the following:\r\n<pre>passenger_root [output #1]\r\npassenger_ruby [output #2]</pre>\r\nDon\'t include those square brackets. Mine looks like this:\r\n<pre>\r\npassenger_root /usr/local/rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p180/gems/passenger-3.0.6\r\npassenger_ruby /usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-12','','','2011-04-11 05:51:55','2011-04-11 05:51:55','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/92/48-revision-12',0,'revision','',0),(93,1,'2011-04-11 05:55:14','2011-04-11 05:55:14','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\r\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\r\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\r\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\r\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). </p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Final Configuration (important)</h1>\r\n<p>We\'re not finished just yet. We will need to tell nginx where to find the Passenger executables and what-not. nginx\'s configuration is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. It\'s a file - open it with whatever text-editor you like (this author sheepishly admits to using nano, having never used a terminal for any significant editing). You\'ll see a whole bunch of stuff in there. Go take a look, look at the nginx documentation if you want to know what some of it does, we\'ll definitely be coming back to it later. We\'re going to add two lines. One will tell nginx where Passenger has its <i>things</i>, the other line will tell nginx where to find a ruby executable for Passenger to use.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s figure out where our passenger root is:\r\n<pre>passenger-config --root</pre>\r\nBam! <tt>passenger-config</tt> should display a path to where Passenger is installed to. Remember this! We shall call it <tt>output #1</tt>. We\'re also going to need to know where our ruby is:\r\n<pre>which ruby</pre>\r\nHooray! We shall call this <tt>output #2</tt>. Now we have the information we need to configure nginx. Look at the following:\r\n<pre>passenger_root [output #1]\r\npassenger_ruby [output #2]</pre>\r\nDon\'t include those square brackets. Mine looks like this:\r\n<pre>\r\npassenger_root /usr/local/rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p180/gems/passenger-3.0.6\r\npassenger_ruby /usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby\r\n</pre>\r\nNow, finally, place those two lines into your <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt> file. Somewhere near the top - outside the <tt>html</tt> block (some would say the <i>top-level</i>). Awesome. Quick! Reload the nginx configuration:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</pre>\r\n','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-13','','','2011-04-11 05:55:14','2011-04-11 05:55:14','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/93/48-revision-13',0,'revision','',0),(94,1,'2011-04-11 05:59:02','2011-04-11 05:59:02','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\r\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\r\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\r\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\r\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). </p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Final Configuration (important)</h1>\r\n<p>We\'re not finished just yet. We will need to tell nginx where to find the Passenger executables and what-not. nginx\'s configuration is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. It\'s a file - open it with whatever text-editor you like (this author sheepishly admits to using nano, having never used a terminal for any significant editing). You\'ll see a whole bunch of stuff in there. Go take a look, look at the nginx documentation if you want to know what some of it does, we\'ll definitely be coming back to it later. We\'re going to add two lines. One will tell nginx where Passenger has its <i>things</i>, the other line will tell nginx where to find a ruby executable for Passenger to use.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s figure out where our passenger root is:\r\n<pre>passenger-config --root</pre>\r\nBam! <tt>passenger-config</tt> should display a path to where Passenger is installed to. Remember this! We shall call it <tt>output #1</tt>. We\'re also going to need to know where our ruby is:\r\n<pre>which ruby</pre>\r\nHooray! We shall call this <tt>output #2</tt>. Now we have the information we need to configure nginx. Look at the following:\r\n<pre>passenger_root [output #1]\r\npassenger_ruby [output #2]</pre>\r\nDon\'t include those square brackets. Mine looks like this:\r\n<pre>\r\npassenger_root /usr/local/rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p180/gems/passenger-3.0.6\r\npassenger_ruby /usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby\r\n</pre>\r\nNow, finally, place those two lines into your <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt> file. Somewhere near the top - outside the <tt>html</tt> block (some would say the <i>top-level</i>). Awesome. Quick! Reload the nginx configuration:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</pre>\r\nAnd breathe.\r\n<h1>Summary</h1>\r\nYou now have nginx with Passenger up and running. You still don\'t have Rails installed, and you have nothing to point your webserver to. We will rectify this shortly.','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-14','','','2011-04-11 05:59:02','2011-04-11 05:59:02','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/94/48-revision-14',0,'revision','',0),(95,1,'2011-04-03 05:19:58','2011-04-03 05:19:58','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivial - but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you too don\'t feel horrendously useless. If, in reality, you <i>are</i> horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So come along, my homies, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Yo, here be ground rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i> (that is, a collection of technologies that will comprise our server). The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul><li>Archlinux</li><li>nginx</li><li>Passenger</li><li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li><li>RVM</li><li>Rails</li></ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, private.</p>\r\n\r\n','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-12','','','2011-04-03 05:19:58','2011-04-03 05:19:58','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/95/22-revision-12',0,'revision','',0),(96,1,'2011-04-04 06:14:04','2011-04-04 06:14:04','<p class=\"overview\">Archlinux is a distribution of Linux that is, to be blunt, hella minimalistic. There are <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">installation instructions </a> already written. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Pacman (waka waka waka)</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t Pacman a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nNo.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora (amongst others) will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means when we\'re ready, we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install, rather than outdated versions. It also means pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p><p>\r\nThis is... pretty much all we need to do to our general Archlinux setup before we begin installing things. Yeah, I was really expecting this page to be longer, too.</p>','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-12','','','2011-04-04 06:14:04','2011-04-04 06:14:04','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/96/35-revision-12',0,'revision','',0),(97,1,'2011-04-11 14:21:06','2011-04-11 14:21:06','<p class=\"overview\">\"Archlinux behooves one to reclaim what the gentry once discarded as commonplace\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rational</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux is a very minimalistic distribution. There is beauty in simplicity. There\'s also less things to go wrong. Think of it as a blank canvas. If we were trying to paint something beautiful on a already-used canvas, we would either have to respect previous elements of said work, or \"reset\" the canvas with paint-stripper or something. I think the analogy is breaking down - much like paint.</p>\r\n<h1>Installation</h1>\r\n<p>There are <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">installation instructions </a> already written. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Pacman (waka waka waka)</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t Pacman a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nNo.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora (amongst others) will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means when we\'re ready, we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install, rather than outdated versions. It also means pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p><p>\r\nThis is... pretty much all we need to do to our general Archlinux setup before we begin installing things. Yeah, I was really expecting this page to be longer, too.</p>','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-13','','','2011-04-11 14:21:06','2011-04-11 14:21:06','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/97/35-revision-13',0,'revision','',0),(98,1,'2011-04-07 07:29:09','2011-04-07 07:29:09','<p class=\"overview\">Before we do anything else, we\'ll get some ruby all up in this machine</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby, well, almost everything ever, actually. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-27','','','2011-04-07 07:29:09','2011-04-07 07:29:09','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/98/54-revision-27',0,'revision','',0),(99,1,'2011-04-11 14:24:32','2011-04-11 14:24:32','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shalt not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\" - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby, well, almost everything ever, actually. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-28','','','2011-04-11 14:24:32','2011-04-11 14:24:32','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/99/54-revision-28',0,'revision','',0),(100,1,'2011-04-11 14:25:00','2011-04-11 14:25:00','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\" - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby, well, almost everything ever, actually. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-29','','','2011-04-11 14:25:00','2011-04-11 14:25:00','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/100/54-revision-29',0,'revision','',0),(101,1,'2011-04-11 14:26:19','2011-04-11 14:26:19','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>RVM - System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>If you don\'t know what RVM is, <a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">I\'m-a drop some knowledge for you, sir</a>. RVM allows us to have multiple versions of Ruby coexisting is harmony on one system. It\'s basically a series of bash scripts. Now, most distros of Linux come with a \"system ruby\" - a Ruby that, er, comes with the system - sometimes seriously out of date. Archlinux has no such thing - we have no Ruby. It helps in that we don\'t have to worry about pathing conflicts with a system-ruby. We are a blank canvas, with our imaginations the only thing between us and revelation.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby, well, almost everything ever, actually. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-30','','','2011-04-11 14:26:19','2011-04-11 14:26:19','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/101/54-revision-30',0,'revision','',0),(102,1,'2011-04-11 14:32:40','2011-04-11 14:32:40','<p class=\"overview\">\"And on the fifth day, the Lord said \'Fuck, why isn\'t this loading correctly?\', and giraffes had six legs\" - Genesis 20:4\r\n\r\n<h1>The what now?</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session - that is, usually, when we log in - there are usually things to do, such as: Adding paths to <tt>PATH</tt>, loading scripts, loading personal settings, and more! Bash does this in two files: <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, and <tt>.bashrc</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. <i>Login shells</i> are shells where you have to log in, such as via ssh, or simply just logging into the machine using the terminal. <i>Interactive non-login shells</i> include such things as opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code> from a pre-existing terminal session; those instances will not require a login. <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Which to pick</h1>\r\n<p>So, one file is chosen over the other depending on how you\'ve started your bash session. Often-times, though, we wish for something to load <i>every</i> time we start a new bash session, regardless of whether or not we\'ve had to log in or not. The almost-unanimous solution is to put that stuff in <tt>.bashrc</tt> and <tt>source ~/.bashrc</tt> from inside <tt>.bash_profile</tt>. (<tt>source</tt> is a bash command that loads and executes the specified script file). Using this solution, we are unable to have something run for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>, but not have it run for <i>login shells</i>. From personal experience, there hasn\'t been a time this has been a problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory, such as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted from <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is minimalistic to the maximum. Because there\'s nothing there (in <tt>/etc/skel</tt>), if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write something in it, whenever we create a new user, the file simply gets copy-pasted, with what we\'ve written in it!</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files: The Story Begins</h1>\r\n<p>For many system-wide installations (such as RVM, amongst others), when following the installation instructions, simply writing the specified code into <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> isn\'t enough. (Let us keep in mind for system-wide installations, we are often root, so <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> is most likely <tt>/root/.bash_profile</tt>). Often, we will be creating new users for various purposes. It would be a hassle to have to set up their profiles to load the scripts and whatnot to use the system-wide tools we\'ve installed. Therefore, when modifying <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> or <tt>~/.bashrc</tt>, make sure to correspondingly change <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt> or <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>. That way, new users can automagically use the system-wide tools, without needing to configure anything.</p>\r\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','publish','open','open','','appendix-a-startup-files-and-you','','','2011-04-18 07:52:36','2011-04-18 07:52:36','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=102',-1,'page','',0),(103,1,'2011-04-11 14:32:23','2011-04-11 14:32:23','','Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision','','','2011-04-11 14:32:23','2011-04-11 14:32:23','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/103/102-revision',0,'revision','',0),(104,1,'2011-04-11 14:32:40','2011-04-11 14:32:40','Pow!','Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-2','','','2011-04-11 14:32:40','2011-04-11 14:32:40','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/104/102-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(105,1,'2011-04-18 05:06:55','2011-04-18 05:06:55','<p class=\"overview\">\"And on the fifth day, the Lord said \'Fuck, why isn\'t this loading correctly?\', and giraffes had six legs\" - Genesis 20:4\n\n<h1>The what now?</h1>\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session - that is, usually, when we log in - there are usually things to do, such as: Adding paths to <tt>PATH</tt>, loading scripts, loading personal settings, and more! Bash does this in two files: <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, and <tt>.bashrc</tt>.</p>\n\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\n<p>There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. <i>Login shells</i> are shells where you have to log in, such as via ssh, or simply just logging into the machine using the terminal. <i>Interactive non-login shells</i> include such things as opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code> from a pre-existing terminal session; those instances will not require a login. <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells.</p>\n\n<h1>Which to pick</h1>\n<p>So, one file is chosen over the other depending on how you\'ve started your bash session. Often-times, though, we wish for something to load <i>every</i> time we start a new bash session, regardless of whether or not we\'ve had to log in or not. The almost-unanimous solution is to put that stuff in <tt>.bashrc</tt> and <tt>source ~/.bashrc</tt> from inside <tt>.bash_profile</tt>. (<tt>source</tt> is a bash command that loads and executes the specified script file). Using this solution, we are unable to have something run for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>, but not have it run for <i>login shells</i>. From personal experience, there hasn\'t been a time this has been a problem.</p>\n\n<h1>Skeleton Files</h1>\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory, such as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted from <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is minimalistic to the maximum. Because there\'s nothing there (in <tt>/etc/skel</tt>), if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write something in it, whenever we create a new user, the file simply gets copy-pasted, with what we\'ve written in it!</p>\n\n<h1>Skeleton Files: The Reprise</h1>\n<p>For many system-wide installations (such as RVM, amongst others), when following the installation instructions, simply writing the specified code into <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> isn\'t enough. (Let us keep in mind for system-wide installations, we are often root, so <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> is most likely <tt>/root/.bash_profile</tt>). Often, we will be creating new users for various purposes. It would be a hassle to have to set up their profiles to load the scripts and whatnot to use the system-wide tools we\'ve installed. Therefore, when modifying <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> or <tt>~/.bashrc</tt>, make sure to correspondingly change <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt> or <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>. That way, new users can automagically use the system-wide tools, without needing to configure anything.</p>\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-autosave','','','2011-04-18 05:06:55','2011-04-18 05:06:55','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/105/102-autosave',0,'revision','',0),(106,1,'2011-04-12 06:25:11','2011-04-12 06:25:11','Pow!','Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-3','','','2011-04-12 06:25:11','2011-04-12 06:25:11','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/106/102-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(107,1,'2011-04-12 06:55:35','2011-04-12 06:55:35','<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are usually things to do. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel