>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-5','','','2011-04-14 07:33:00','2011-04-14 07:33:00','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/108/102-revision-5',0,'revision','',0),(109,1,'2011-04-14 07:38:11','2011-04-14 07:38:11','<p class=\"overview\">\"Let it not be said that no man shall start in life as his predecessors ended theirs\" - Alec Baldwin</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are usually things to do. Things such as: adding paths to <tt>PATH</tt>, loading scripts (RVM!), loading personal settings, and more! Bash does this in two files, your <tt>bash profile</tt>, and your <tt>bashrc file</tt>. \r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-6','','','2011-04-14 07:38:11','2011-04-14 07:38:11','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/109/102-revision-6',0,'revision','',0),(110,1,'2011-04-14 07:39:30','2011-04-14 07:39:30','<p class=\"overview\">\"Let it not be said that no man shall start in life as his predecessors ended theirs\" - Alec Baldwin</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The what now?</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are usually things to do. Things such as: adding paths to <tt>PATH</tt>, loading scripts (RVM!), loading personal settings, and more! Bash does this in two files, your <tt>bash profile</tt>, and your <tt>bashrc file</tt>. \r\n\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-7','','','2011-04-14 07:39:30','2011-04-14 07:39:30','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/110/102-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(111,1,'2011-04-18 04:40:05','2011-04-18 04:40:05','<p class=\"overview\">\"Let it not be said that no man shall start in life as his predecessors ended theirs\" - Alec Baldwin</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The what now?</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are usually things to do. Things such as: adding paths to <tt>PATH</tt>, loading scripts (RVM!), loading personal settings, and more! Bash does this in two files: <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, and <tt>.bashrc</tt>. \r\n\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. <i>Login shells</i> are shells where you have to log in, such as via ssh, or simply just logging into the machine (via terminal, obviously). <i>Interactive non-login shells</i> include such things as opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code> from a pre-existing terminal session; those instances will not require a login. <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells.\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-8','','','2011-04-18 04:40:05','2011-04-18 04:40:05','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/111/102-revision-8',0,'revision','',0),(112,1,'2011-04-18 04:42:59','2011-04-18 04:42:59','<p class=\"overview\">\"Let it not be said that no man shall start in life as his predecessors ended theirs\" - Alec Baldwin</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The what now?</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session - that is, when we log in - there are usually things to do, such as: Adding paths to <tt>PATH</tt>, loading scripts (RVM!), loading personal settings, and more! Bash does this in two files: <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, and <tt>.bashrc</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. <i>Login shells</i> are shells where you have to log in, such as via ssh, or simply just logging into the machine (via terminal, obviously). <i>Interactive non-login shells</i> include such things as opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code> from a pre-existing terminal session; those instances will not require a login. <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-9','','','2011-04-18 04:42:59','2011-04-18 04:42:59','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/112/102-revision-9',0,'revision','',0),(113,1,'2011-04-18 04:45:48','2011-04-18 04:45:48','<p class=\"overview\">\"And on the fifth day, the Lord said \'Fuck, why isn\'t this loading correctly?\', and giraffes had six legs\" - Genesis 20:4\r\n\r\n<h1>The what now?</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session - that is, when we log in - there are usually things to do, such as: Adding paths to <tt>PATH</tt>, loading scripts (RVM!), loading personal settings, and more! Bash does this in two files: <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, and <tt>.bashrc</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. <i>Login shells</i> are shells where you have to log in, such as via ssh, or simply just logging into the machine using the terminal. <i>Interactive non-login shells</i> include such things as opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code> from a pre-existing terminal session; those instances will not require a login. <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-10','','','2011-04-18 04:45:48','2011-04-18 04:45:48','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/113/102-revision-10',0,'revision','',0),(114,1,'2011-04-18 04:55:50','2011-04-18 04:55:50','<p class=\"overview\">\"And on the fifth day, the Lord said \'Fuck, why isn\'t this loading correctly?\', and giraffes had six legs\" - Genesis 20:4\r\n\r\n<h1>The what now?</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session - that is, usually, when we log in - there are usually things to do, such as: Adding paths to <tt>PATH</tt>, loading scripts, loading personal settings, and more! Bash does this in two files: <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, and <tt>.bashrc</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. <i>Login shells</i> are shells where you have to log in, such as via ssh, or simply just logging into the machine using the terminal. <i>Interactive non-login shells</i> include such things as opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code> from a pre-existing terminal session; those instances will not require a login. <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Which to pick</h1>\r\n<p>So, one file is chosen over the other depending on how you\'ve started your bash session. Often-times, though, we wish for something to load <i>every</i> time we start a new bash session, regardless of whether or not we\'ve had to log in or not. The almost-unanimous solution is to put that stuff in <tt>.bashrc</tt> and <tt>source ~/.bashrc</tt> from inside <tt>.bash_profile</tt>. (<tt>source</tt> is a bash command that loads and executes the specified script file). Using this solution, we are unable to have something run for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>, but not have it run for <i>login shells</i>. From personal experience, there hasn\'t been a time this has been a problem. \r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-11','','','2011-04-18 04:55:50','2011-04-18 04:55:50','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/114/102-revision-11',0,'revision','',0),(115,1,'2011-04-18 05:04:52','2011-04-18 05:04:52','<p class=\"overview\">\"And on the fifth day, the Lord said \'Fuck, why isn\'t this loading correctly?\', and giraffes had six legs\" - Genesis 20:4\r\n\r\n<h1>The what now?</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session - that is, usually, when we log in - there are usually things to do, such as: Adding paths to <tt>PATH</tt>, loading scripts, loading personal settings, and more! Bash does this in two files: <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, and <tt>.bashrc</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. <i>Login shells</i> are shells where you have to log in, such as via ssh, or simply just logging into the machine using the terminal. <i>Interactive non-login shells</i> include such things as opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code> from a pre-existing terminal session; those instances will not require a login. <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Which to pick</h1>\r\n<p>So, one file is chosen over the other depending on how you\'ve started your bash session. Often-times, though, we wish for something to load <i>every</i> time we start a new bash session, regardless of whether or not we\'ve had to log in or not. The almost-unanimous solution is to put that stuff in <tt>.bashrc</tt> and <tt>source ~/.bashrc</tt> from inside <tt>.bash_profile</tt>. (<tt>source</tt> is a bash command that loads and executes the specified script file). Using this solution, we are unable to have something run for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>, but not have it run for <i>login shells</i>. From personal experience, there hasn\'t been a time this has been a problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory, such as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted from <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is minimalistic to the maximum. Because there\'s nothing there (in <tt>/etc/skel</tt>), if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write something in it, whenever we create a new user, the file simply gets copy-pasted, with what we\'ve written in it!</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files: The Repose</h1>\r\n<p>For many system-wide installations (such as RVM, amongst others), when following the installation instructions, simply writing the specified code into <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> isn\'t enough. (Let us keep in mind for system-wide installations, we are often root, so <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> is most likely <tt>/root/.bash_profile</tt>). Often, we will be creating new users for various purposes. It would be a hassle to have to set up their profiles to load the scripts and whatnot to use the system-wide tools we\'ve installed. Therefore, when modifying <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> or <tt>~/.bashrc</tt>, make sure to correspondingly change <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt> or <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>. That way, new users can automagically use the system-wide tools, without needing to configure anything.</p>\r\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-12','','','2011-04-18 05:04:52','2011-04-18 05:04:52','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/115/102-revision-12',0,'revision','',0),(116,1,'2011-04-18 05:18:09','2011-04-18 05:18:09','<p class=\"overview\">\"And on the fifth day, the Lord said \'Fuck, why isn\'t this loading correctly?\', and giraffes had six legs\" - Genesis 20:4\r\n\r\n<h1>The what now?</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session - that is, usually, when we log in - there are usually things to do, such as: Adding paths to <tt>PATH</tt>, loading scripts, loading personal settings, and more! Bash does this in two files: <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, and <tt>.bashrc</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. <i>Login shells</i> are shells where you have to log in, such as via ssh, or simply just logging into the machine using the terminal. <i>Interactive non-login shells</i> include such things as opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code> from a pre-existing terminal session; those instances will not require a login. <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Which to pick</h1>\r\n<p>So, one file is chosen over the other depending on how you\'ve started your bash session. Often-times, though, we wish for something to load <i>every</i> time we start a new bash session, regardless of whether or not we\'ve had to log in or not. The almost-unanimous solution is to put that stuff in <tt>.bashrc</tt> and <tt>source ~/.bashrc</tt> from inside <tt>.bash_profile</tt>. (<tt>source</tt> is a bash command that loads and executes the specified script file). Using this solution, we are unable to have something run for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>, but not have it run for <i>login shells</i>. From personal experience, there hasn\'t been a time this has been a problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory, such as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted from <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is minimalistic to the maximum. Because there\'s nothing there (in <tt>/etc/skel</tt>), if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write something in it, whenever we create a new user, the file simply gets copy-pasted, with what we\'ve written in it!</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files: The Reprise</h1>\r\n<p>For many system-wide installations (such as RVM, amongst others), when following the installation instructions, simply writing the specified code into <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> isn\'t enough. (Let us keep in mind for system-wide installations, we are often root, so <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> is most likely <tt>/root/.bash_profile</tt>). Often, we will be creating new users for various purposes. It would be a hassle to have to set up their profiles to load the scripts and whatnot to use the system-wide tools we\'ve installed. Therefore, when modifying <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt> or <tt>~/.bashrc</tt>, make sure to correspondingly change <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt> or <tt>/etc/skel/.bashrc</tt>. That way, new users can automagically use the system-wide tools, without needing to configure anything.</p>\r\n','Appendix A: Startup Files and You','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-13','','','2011-04-18 05:18:09','2011-04-18 05:18:09','',102,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/116/102-revision-13',0,'revision','',0),(117,1,'2011-04-11 14:30:39','2011-04-11 14:30:39','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\r\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. So... let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n<h1>Startup Files and You</h1>\r\n<p>Whenever we load a bash session (login), there are some things we need to <i>load</i>. For example, with RVM, we need RVM to set up the symlinks to point to the default version of Ruby we\'ve chosen (more on this later). But <i>before</i> we can do that, we have to load RVM itself; we have to tell our system where the scripts are. The line we have to add is simple:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nWe\'ll be referring to this \"the line\". It tells bash to run the file at <tt>/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm</tt>. Now, we want this command to run whenever we log in (so it works if we have multiple terminals up). It would obviously go in our <tt>.bash_profile</tt> then. And yes, it should. But wait! We\'re root <i>now</i>, but we won\'t stay root - it\'s not very safe. At some point, we\'ll make a user account to set up the hosting of the website. And they\'ll need that line in their <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file too.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Skeleton Files To The Rescue</h1>\r\n<p>In Linux, when you create a new user, often a set of default files will be placed in their home directory. Such files as <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, <tt>.bashrc</tt>, etc. Where do these files come from? They are copy-pasted <tt>/etc/skel</tt>. Archlinux doesn\'t come with anything in <tt>/etc/skel</tt> though, because it is \"hella minimalistic\". Because there\'s nothing there, if we were to create a new user, the new user would lack a <tt>.bash_profile</tt> file, amongst others. They\'d have to create one, and add the line above, to be able to use RVM. Magically, if we create <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>, and write the line in it, whenever we create a new user, it simply gets copy-pasted, and they can use RVM without doing anything!</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"aside\">\r\n<h1><tt>.bash_profile</tt> and <tt>.bashrc</tt></h1>\r\n<p>These two files are used by Linuxes to configure things when you log in and such. There are two files because they are run at different times. One is for <i>logins shells</i>, and the other is for <i>interactive non-login shells</i>. In English, shells where you have to log in (ssh, just logging in on the machine), and shells where you don\'t (opening a new terminal inside Gnome or KDE, or running <code>/bin/bash</code>). <code>.bash_profile</code> is used for the <i>login</i> shells, and <code>.bashrc</code> is used for the <i>non-login</i> shells. Here is a <a href=\"http://www.joshstaiger.org/archives/2005/07/bash_profile_vs.html\">more detailed explanation</a>. </p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby, well, almost everything ever, actually. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-31','','','2011-04-11 14:30:39','2011-04-11 14:30:39','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/117/54-revision-31',0,'revision','',0),(118,1,'2011-04-19 06:10:29','2011-04-19 06:10:29','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\r\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. So... let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will 