cally. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-32','','','2011-04-19 06:10:29','2011-04-19 06:10:29','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/118/54-revision-32',0,'revision','',0),(119,1,'2011-04-19 06:11:20','2011-04-19 06:11:20','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\r\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. So... let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby, well, almost everything ever, actually. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-33','','','2011-04-19 06:11:20','2011-04-19 06:11:20','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/119/54-revision-33',0,'revision','',0),(120,1,'2011-04-19 06:17:08','2011-04-19 06:17:08','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\r\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. So... let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>on_load</h1>\r\n<p>When we login, we\'ll need to initialise RVM, with the following line placed in one of our <a href=\"articles/basic-server-management-for-hackers/appendix-a-startup-files\">startup files</a>:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\n<i>Remember</i>: We need to place the line in both <tt>/root/</tt> and <tt>/etc/skel/</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby, well, almost everything ever, actually. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-34','','','2011-04-19 06:17:08','2011-04-19 06:17:08','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/120/54-revision-34',0,'revision','',0),(121,1,'2011-04-19 06:26:03','2011-04-19 06:26:03','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\r\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. So... let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>OnLoad</h1>\r\n<p>When we login, we\'ll need to initialise RVM, with the following line placed in one of our <a href=\"appendix-a-startup-files\">startup files</a>:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\n<i>Remember</i>: We need to place the line in both <tt>/root/</tt> and <tt>/etc/skel/</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby, well, almost everything ever, actually. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-35','','','2011-04-19 06:26:03','2011-04-19 06:26:03','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/121/54-revision-35',0,'revision','',0),(122,1,'2011-04-19 06:27:33','2011-04-19 06:27:33','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\r\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. So... let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>OnLoad</h1>\r\n<p>When we login, we\'ll need to initialise RVM, with the following line placed in one of our <a href=\"appendix-a-startup-files\">startup files</a>:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nMake sure you\'ve read the appendix on startup-files! You\'ll probably want to place the line in <tt>.bashsrc</tt>, and source <tt>.bashrc</tt> from <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, like most configurations. <i>Remember</i>: We need to place the line in both <tt>/root/</tt> and <tt>/etc/skel/</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby, well, almost everything ever, actually. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-36','','','2011-04-19 06:27:33','2011-04-19 06:27:33','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/122/54-revision-36',0,'revision','',0),(123,1,'2011-04-11 14:14:48','2011-04-11 14:14:48','<p class=\"overview\">\"If you wish to make an apple pie from scratch, you must first invent the universe\" - Carl Sagan</p>\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\r\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\r\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\r\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\r\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). </p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Final Configuration (important)</h1>\r\n<p>We\'re not finished just yet. We will need to tell nginx where to find the Passenger executables and what-not. nginx\'s configuration is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. It\'s a file - open it with whatever text-editor you like (this author sheepishly admits to using nano, having never used a terminal for any significant editing). You\'ll see a whole bunch of stuff in there. Go take a look, look at the nginx documentation if you want to know what some of it does, we\'ll definitely be coming back to it later. We\'re going to add two lines. One will tell nginx where Passenger has its <i>things</i>, the other line will tell nginx where to find a ruby executable for Passenger to use.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s figure out where our passenger root is:\r\n<pre>passenger-config --root</pre>\r\nBam! <tt>passenger-config</tt> should display a path to where Passenger is installed to. Remember this! We shall call it <tt>output #1</tt>. We\'re also going to need to know where our ruby is:\r\n<pre>which ruby</pre>\r\nHooray! We shall call this <tt>output #2</tt>. Now we have the information we need to configure nginx. Look at the following:\r\n<pre>passenger_root [output #1]\r\npassenger_ruby [output #2]</pre>\r\nDon\'t include those square brackets. Mine looks like this:\r\n<pre>\r\npassenger_root /usr/local/rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p180/gems/passenger-3.0.6\r\npassenger_ruby /usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby\r\n</pre>\r\nNow, finally, place those two lines into your <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt> file. Somewhere near the top - outside the <tt>html</tt> block (some would say the <i>top-level</i>). Awesome. Quick! Reload the nginx configuration:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</pre>\r\nAnd breathe.\r\n<h1>Summary</h1>\r\nYou now have nginx with Passenger up and running. You still don\'t have Rails installed, and you have nothing to point your webserver to. We will rectify this shortly.','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-15','','','2011-04-11 14:14:48','2011-04-11 14:14:48','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/123/48-revision-15',0,'revision','',0),(124,1,'2011-04-19 06:29:53','2011-04-19 06:29:53','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\r\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. So... let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>OnLoad</h1>\r\n<p>When we login, we\'ll need to initialise RVM, with the following line placed in one of our <a href=\"appendix-a-startup-files\">startup files</a>:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nMake sure you\'ve read the appendix on startup-files! You\'ll probably want to place the line in <tt>.bashsrc</tt>, and source <tt>.bashrc</tt> from <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, like most configurations. <i>Remember</i>: We need to place the line in both <tt>/root/</tt> and <tt>/etc/skel/</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby - indeed, they will compile the vast majority of packages we install. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-37','','','2011-04-19 06:29:53','2011-04-19 06:29:53','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/124/54-revision-37',0,'revision','',0),(125,1,'2011-04-19 07:00:24','2011-04-19 07:00:24','<p class=\"overview\">\"To serve one\'s country - that is the dream. That, and occasionally a very naughty nurse\" - Voltaire</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\r\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\r\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\r\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\r\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). </p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Final Configuration (important)</h1>\r\n<p>We\'re not finished just yet. We will need to tell nginx where to find the Passenger executables and what-not. nginx\'s configuration is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. It\'s a file - open it with whatever text-editor you like (this author sheepishly admits to using nano, having never used a terminal for any significant editing). You\'ll see a whole bunch of stuff in there. Go take a look, look at the nginx documentation if you want to know what some of it does, we\'ll definitely be coming back to it later. We\'re going to add two lines. One will tell nginx where Passenger has its <i>things</i>, the other line will tell nginx where to find a ruby executable for Passenger to use.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s figure out where our passenger root is:\r\n<pre>passenger-config --root</pre>\r\nBam! <tt>passenger-config</tt> should display a path to where Passenger is installed to. Remember this! We shall call it <tt>output #1</tt>. We\'re also going to need to know where our ruby is:\r\n<pre>which ruby</pre>\r\nHooray! We shall call this <tt>output #2</tt>. Now we have the information we need to configure nginx. Look at the following:\r\n<pre>passenger_root [output #1]\r\npassenger_ruby [output #2]</pre>\r\nDon\'t include those square brackets. Mine looks like this:\r\n<pre>\r\npassenger_root /usr/local/rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p180/gems/passenger-3.0.6\r\npassenger_ruby /usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby\r\n</pre>\r\nNow, finally, place those two lines into your <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt> file. Somewhere near the top - outside the <tt>html</tt> block (some would say the <i>top-level</i>). Awesome. Quick! Reload the nginx configuration:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</pre>\r\nAnd breathe.\r\n<h1>Summary</h1>\r\nYou now have nginx with Passenger up and running. You still don\'t have Rails installed, and you have nothing to point your webserver to. We will rectify this shortly.','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-16','','','2011-04-19 07:00:24','2011-04-19 07:00:24','',48,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/125/48-revision-16',0,'revision','',0),(126,1,'2011-04-19 07:04:49','2011-04-19 07:04:49','<p class=\"overview\">\"I happened upon a man who had not yet heard of databases - his face was free of worry, his brow bore no furrows of misunderstanding, and his demeanour was pleasant\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Overview</h1>\r\n<p>We\'ll go over the installation of a bunch of different databases. They\'re all very simple to install. Configuring your application to utilise them is a different story, and will be discussed later.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>MySQL</h1>\r\n<p>Let\'s start with the de-facto standard, then. <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL\">MySQL for Archlinux</a> is very easy to set up:\r\n<pre>pacman -S mysql</pre>\r\nPow, done. Now, since this is a production machine, we\'ll want to make it secure. MySQL provides a script to help us with this. We need to start the daemon first though:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/mysqld start && mysql_secure_installation</pre>\r\nHit Enter for the first question, because we haven\'t given the root account a password yet. Then, set the password for root. Disable anonymous access, disable remote login via root, and remove the test database. This is a production machine, and we have control over our root account - we can do <i>anything</i>; we do not need these things designed for a development machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>MongoDB</h1>\r\n<p>I use MongoDB for my projects, so I\'ll include this here. MongoDB is <i>also</i> very easy to setup:\r\n<pre>pacman -S mongodb</pre>\r\nThis will probably install a bunch (maybe four) things alongside mongodb - it\'s all good! Remember to start it:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/mongodb start</pre>\r\n</p>','Databases','','publish','open','open','','databases','','','2011-04-28 08:22:44','2011-04-28 08:22:44','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=126',3,'page','',0),(127,1,'2011-04-19 07:04:42','2011-04-19 07:04:42','','Rails','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision','','','2011-04-19 07:04:42','2011-04-19 07:04:42','',126,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/127/126-revision',0,'revision','',0),(128,1,'2011-04-21 07:07:38','2011-04-21 07:07:38','<p class=\"overview\">\"I happened upon a man who had not yet heard of databases - his face was free of worry, his brow bore no furrows of misunderstanding, and his demeanour was pleasant\" - Mark Twain</p>\n\n<h1>Overview</h1>\n<p>We\'ll go over the installation of a bunch of different databases. They\'re all very simple to install. Configuring your application to utilise them is a different story, and will be discussed later.</p>\n\n<h1>MySQL</h1>\n<p>Let\'s start with the de-facto standard, then. <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL\">MySQL for Archlinux</a> is very easy to set up:\n<pre>pacman -S mysql</pre>\nPow, done. Now, since this is a production machine, we\'ll want to make it secure. MySQL provides a script to help us with this. We need to start the daemon first though:\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/mysqld start && mysql_secure_installation</pre>\nHit Enter for the first question, because we haven\'t given the root account a password yet. Then, set the password for root. Disable anonymous access, disable remote login via root, and remove the test database. This is a production machine, and we have control over our root account - we can do <i>anything</i>; we do not need these things designed for a development machine.</p>\n\n<h1>MongoDB</h1>\n<p>I use MongoDB for my projects, so I\'ll include this here. MongoDB is <i>also</i> very easy to setup:\n<pre>pacman -Ss mongodb</pre>\nThis will probably install a bunch (maybe four) things alongside mongodb - it\'s all good! Since MongoDB','Databases','','inherit','open','open','','126-autosave','','','2011-04-21 07:07:38','2011-04-21 07:07:38','',126,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/128/126-autosave',0,'revision','',0),(129,1,'2011-04-19 07:04:49','2011-04-19 07:04:49','','Rails','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-2','','','2011-04-19 07:04:49','2011-04-19 07:04:49','',126,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/129/126-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(130,1,'2011-04-20 06:13:48','2011-04-20 06:13:48','<p class=\"overview\">\"I once met a man who had not heard of databases - his face was free of worry, his brow bore no furrows of misunderstanding, and his demeanour was pleasant\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Overview</h1>\r\n<p>We\'ll go over the installation of a bunch of different databases. They\'re all very simple to install. Configuring your application to utilise them is a different story, and will be discussed later.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>MySQL</h1>\r\n<p>Let\'s start with the de-facto standard, then. <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL\">MySQL for Archlinux</a> is very easy to set up:\r\n<pre>pacman -S mysql</pre>\r\nPow, done. Now, since this is a production machine, we\'ll want to make it secure. MySQL provides a script to help us with this. We need to start the daemon first though:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/mysqld start && mysql_secure_installation</pre>\r\nHit Enter for the first question, because we haven\'t given the root account a password yet. The, set the password for root. Disable anonymous access, disable root login remotely, and remove the test database. This is a production machine, and we have control over our root account - we can do <i>anything</i>, we do not need these things designed for a development machine.','Databases','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-3','','','2011-04-20 06:13:48','2011-04-20 06:13:48','',126,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/130/126-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(131,1,'2011-04-20 06:14:01','2011-04-20 06:14:01','<p class=\"overview\">\"I once met a man who had not heard of databases - his face was free of worry, his brow bore no furrows of misunderstanding, and his demeanour was pleasant\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Overview</h1>\r\n<p>We\'ll go over the installation of a bunch of different databases. They\'re all very simple to install. Configuring your application to utilise them is a different story, and will be discussed later.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>MySQL</h1>\r\n<p>Let\'s start with the de-facto standard, then. <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL\">MySQL for Archlinux</a> is very easy to set up:\r\n<pre>pacman -S mysql</pre>\r\nPow, done. Now, since this is a production machine, we\'ll want to make it secure. MySQL provides a script to help us with this. We need to start the daemon first though:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/mysqld start && mysql_secure_installation</pre>\r\nHit Enter for the first question, because we haven\'t given the root account a password yet. The, set the password for root. Disable anonymous access, disable root login remotely, and remove the test database. This is a production machine, and we have control over our root account - we can do <i>anything</i>, we do not need these things designed for a development machine.','Databases','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-4','','','2011-04-20 06:14:01','2011-04-20 06:14:01','',126,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/131/126-revision-4',0,'revision','',0),(132,1,'2011-04-20 06:15:11','2011-04-20 06:15:11','<p class=\"overview\">\"I once met a man who had not heard of databases - his face was free of worry, his brow bore no furrows of misunderstanding, and his demeanour was pleasant\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Overview</h1>\r\n<p>We\'ll go over the installation of a bunch of different databases. They\'re all very simple to install. Configuring your application to utilise them is a different story, and will be discussed later.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>MySQL</h1>\r\n<p>Let\'s start with the de-facto standard, then. <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL\">MySQL for Archlinux</a> is very easy to set up:\r\n<pre>pacman -S mysql</pre>\r\nPow, done. Now, since this is a production machine, we\'ll want to make it secure. MySQL provides a script to help us with this. We need to start the daemon first though:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/mysqld start && mysql_secure_installation</pre>\r\nHit Enter for the first question, because we haven\'t given the root account a password yet. Then, set the password for root. Disable anonymous access, disable remote login via root, and remove the test database. This is a production machine, and we have control over our root account - we can do <i>anything</i>; we do not need these things designed for a development machine.','Databases','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-5','','','2011-04-20 06:15:11','2011-04-20 06:15:11','',126,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/132/126-revision-5',0,'revision','',0),(133,1,'2011-04-20 06:16:03','2011-04-20 06:16:03','<p class=\"overview\">\"I happened upon a man who had not yet heard of databases - his face was free of worry, his brow bore no furrows of misunderstanding, and his demeanour was pleasant\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Overview</h1>\r\n<p>We\'ll go over the installation of a bunch of different databases. They\'re all very simple to install. Configuring your application to utilise them is a different story, and will be discussed later.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>MySQL</h1>\r\n<p>Let\'s start with the de-facto standard, then. <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL\">MySQL for Archlinux</a> is very easy to set up:\r\n<pre>pacman -S mysql</pre>\r\nPow, done. Now, since this is a production machine, we\'ll want to make it secure. MySQL provides a script to help us with this. We need to start the daemon first though:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/mysqld start && mysql_secure_installation</pre>\r\nHit Enter for the first question, because we haven\'t given the root account a password yet. Then, set the password for root. Disable anonymous access, disable remote login via root, and remove the test database. This is a production machine, and we have control over our root account - we can do <i>anything</i>; we do not need these things designed for a development machine.','Databases','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-6','','','2011-04-20 06:16:03','2011-04-20 06:16:03','',126,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/133/126-revision-6',0,'revision','',0),(134,1,'2011-04-11 14:21:18','2011-04-11 14:21:18','<p class=\"overview\">\"Archlinux behooves one to reclaim what the gentry once discarded as commonplace\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux is a very minimalistic distribution. There is beauty in simplicity. There\'s also less things to go wrong. Think of it as a blank canvas. If we were trying to paint something beautiful on a already-used canvas, we would either have to respect previous elements of said work, or \"reset\" the canvas with paint-stripper or something. I think the analogy is breaking down - much like paint.</p>\r\n<h1>Installation</h1>\r\n<p>There are <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">installation instructions </a> already written. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Pacman (waka waka waka)</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t Pacman a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nNo.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora (amongst others) will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means when we\'re ready, we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install, rather than outdated versions. It also means pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p><p>\r\nThis is... pretty much all we need to do to our general Archlinux setup before we begin installing things. Yeah, I was really expecting this page to be longer, too.</p>','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-14','','','2011-04-11 14:21:18','2011-04-11 14:21:18','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/134/35-revision-14',0,'revision','',0),(135,1,'2011-04-21 07:15:35','2011-04-21 07:15:35','<p class=\"overview\">\"Archlinux behooves one to reclaim what the gentry once discarded as commonplace\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux is a very minimalistic distribution. There is beauty in simplicity. There\'s also less things to go wrong. Think of it as a blank canvas. If we were trying to paint something beautiful on a already-used canvas, we would either have to respect previous elements of said work, or \"reset\" the canvas with paint-stripper or something. I think the analogy is breaking down - much like paint.</p>\r\n<h1>Installation</h1>\r\n<p>There are <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">installation instructions </a> already written. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Pacman (waka waka waka)</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t Pacman a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nNo.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora (amongst others) will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means when we\'re ready, we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install, rather than outdated versions. It also means pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p><p>\r\n<h1>Watching Me, Watching You</h1>\r\n<p>Now is a <i>very</i> good time to change your mirror. Archlinux\'s mirrorlist is located at <tt>/etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist</tt>. It defaults to a USA server; you may live outside the USA. Find the server listed that is the best fit, and remove the hashes from the front. You can put hashes in front of the USA server if you so choose. Right up the top is a mirrorlist that is as official as you can get (i.e., all current packages will be there - avoiding delays in replication across the other mirrors). It\'s your choice. I went with one in Australia, because that is where I live. Also, it\'s pretty up to date.</p>\r\nThis is... pretty much all we need to do to our general Archlinux setup before we begin installing things. Yeah, I was really expecting this page to be longer, too.</p>','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-15','','','2011-04-21 07:15:35','2011-04-21 07:15:35','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/135/35-revision-15',0,'revision','',0),(136,1,'2011-04-21 07:17:56','2011-04-21 07:17:56','<p class=\"overview\">\"Archlinux behooves one to reclaim what the gentry once discarded as commonplace\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux is a very minimalistic distribution. There is beauty in simplicity. There\'s also less things to go wrong. Think of it as a blank canvas. If we were trying to paint something beautiful on a already-used canvas, we would either have to respect previous elements of said work, or \"reset\" the canvas with paint-stripper or something. I think the analogy is breaking down - much like paint.</p>\r\n<h1>Installation</h1>\r\n<p>There are <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">installation instructions </a> already written. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Pacman (waka waka waka)</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t Pacman a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nNo.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora (amongst others) will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means when we\'re ready, we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install, rather than outdated versions. It also means pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p><p>\r\n<h1>Watching Me, Watching You</h1>\r\n<p>Now is a <i>very</i> good time to change your mirror. Archlinux\'s mirrorlist is located at <tt>/etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist</tt>. It defaults to a USA server; you may live outside the USA. Find the server listed that is the best fit, and remove the hashes from the front. You can put hashes in front of the USA server if you so choose. Right up the top is a mirrorlist that is as official as you can get (i.e., all current packages will be there - avoiding delays in replication across the other mirrors). It\'s your choice. I went with one in Australia, because that is where I live. Also, it\'s pretty up to date.</p>\r\n<p>After you\'ve done this, resync the databases, and update the system:\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nIf you\'re asked to upgrade the database by running a script, run said script. Then <pre>pacman -Syu</pre> again. For safety\'s sake. At this point, you have a system that\'s good to go.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is... pretty much all we need to do to our general Archlinux setup before we begin installing things. Yeah, I was really expecting this page to be longer, too.</p>\r\n','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-16','','','2011-04-21 07:17:56','2011-04-21 07:17:56','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/136/35-revision-16',0,'revision','',0),(137,1,'2011-04-21 07:18:23','2011-04-21 07:18:23','<p class=\"overview\">\"Archlinux behooves one to reclaim what the gentry once discarded as commonplace\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux is a very minimalistic distribution. There is beauty in simplicity. There\'s also less things to go wrong. Think of it as a blank canvas. If we were trying to paint something beautiful on a already-used canvas, we would either have to respect previous elements of said work, or \"reset\" the canvas with paint-stripper or something. I think the analogy is breaking down - much like paint.</p>\r\n<h1>Installation</h1>\r\n<p>There are <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">installation instructions </a> already written. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Pacman (waka waka waka)</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t Pacman a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nNo.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora (amongst others) will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means when we\'re ready, we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install, rather than outdated versions. It also means pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p><p>\r\n<h1>Watching Me, Watching You</h1>\r\n<p>Now is a <i>very</i> good time to change your mirror. Archlinux\'s mirrorlist is located at <tt>/etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist</tt>. It defaults to a USA server; you may live outside the USA. Find the server listed that is the best fit, and remove the hashes from the front. You can put hashes in front of the USA server if you so choose. Right up the top is a mirrorlist that is as official as you can get (i.e., all current packages will be there - avoiding delays in replication across the other mirrors). It\'s your choice. I went with one in Australia, because that is where I live. Also, it\'s pretty up to date.</p>\r\n<p>After you\'ve done this, resync the databases, and update the system:\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nIf you\'re asked to upgrade the database by running a script, run said script. Then <tt>pacman -Syu</tt> again. For safety\'s sake. At this point, you have a system that\'s good to go.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is... pretty much all we need to do to our general Archlinux setup before we begin installing things. Yeah, I was really expecting this page to be longer, too.</p>\r\n','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-17','','','2011-04-21 07:18:23','2011-04-21 07:18:23','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/137/35-revision-17',0,'revision','',0),(138,1,'2011-04-21 07:18:42','2011-04-21 07:18:42','<p class=\"overview\">\"Archlinux behooves one to reclaim what the gentry once discarded as commonplace\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>Archlinux is a very minimalistic distribution. There is beauty in simplicity. There\'s also less things to go wrong. Think of it as a blank canvas. If we were trying to paint something beautiful on a already-used canvas, we would either have to respect previous elements of said work, or \"reset\" the canvas with paint-stripper or something. I think the analogy is breaking down - much like paint.</p>\r\n<h1>Installation</h1>\r\n<p>There are <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Arch_Linux_Install_Guide\">installation instructions </a> already written. Once you\'ve booted into it as root, we\'re good to go. My initial setup was a Rackspace image (hosted on Rackspace, suprisingly). I sshed into it, as root. You can do the same, or install it on a machine you\'re actually in possession of, if you\'re that way inclined. I really don\'t care - as long as you\'ve logged in as root, we can begin our mystical journey together.</p>\r\n<h1>Pacman (waka waka waka)</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nWhat have we done?! What is going on? Isn\'t Pacman a game?\r\n</p><p>\r\nNo.</p><p>\r\n<tt><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacman_(package_manager)\">pacman</a></tt> is the name of Archlinux\'s package manager - it is unique and fundamental to Archlinux. Most of us from Ubuntu or Fedora (amongst others) will be familiar with <tt>apt-get</tt> or <tt>yum</tt>. The details are (vastly) different, but the end result is the same - it will install and remove and update packages just like we\'re used to. The <i>actual</i> command we\'ve run is to do a <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman#Upgrading_packages\">system update</a>. It\'s going to sync the repositories and update the system. This means when we\'re ready, we\'ll be grabbing the latest and greatest versions of the packages we wish to install, rather than outdated versions. It also means pacman will be the latest stable version - it\'s a good thing.</p><p>\r\n<h1>Watching Me, Watching You</h1>\r\n<p>Now is a <i>very</i> good time to change your mirror. Archlinux\'s mirrorlist is located at <tt>/etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist</tt>. It defaults to a USA server; you may live outside the USA. Find the server listed that is the best fit, and remove the hashes from the front. You can put hashes in front of the USA server if you so choose. Right up the top is a mirrorlist that is as official as you can get (i.e., all current packages will be there - avoiding delays in replication across the other mirrors). It\'s your choice. I went with one in Australia, because that is where I live. Also, it\'s pretty up to date.</p>\r\n<p>After you\'ve done this, resync the databases, and update the system:\r\n<pre>pacman -Syu</pre>\r\nIf you\'re asked to upgrade the database by running a script, run said script. Then <tt>pacman -Syu</tt> again. For safety\'s sake. At this point, you have a system that\'s good to go.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Hooray!</h1>\r\n<p>This is... pretty much all we need to do to our general Archlinux setup before we begin installing things. Yeah, I was really expecting this page to be longer, too.</p>\r\n','archlinux','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-18','','','2011-04-21 07:18:42','2011-04-21 07:18:42','',35,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/138/35-revision-18',0,'revision','',0),(140,1,'2011-04-21 07:08:25','2011-04-21 07:08:25','<p class=\"overview\">\"I happened upon a man who had not yet heard of databases - his face was free of worry, his brow bore no furrows of misunderstanding, and his demeanour was pleasant\" - Mark Twain</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Overview</h1>\r\n<p>We\'ll go over the installation of a bunch of different databases. They\'re all very simple to install. Configuring your application to utilise them is a different story, and will be discussed later.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>MySQL</h1>\r\n<p>Let\'s start with the de-facto standard, then. <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL\">MySQL for Archlinux</a> is very easy to set up:\r\n<pre>pacman -S mysql</pre>\r\nPow, done. Now, since this is a production machine, we\'ll want to make it secure. MySQL provides a script to help us with this. We need to start the daemon first though:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/mysqld start && mysql_secure_installation</pre>\r\nHit Enter for the first question, because we haven\'t given the root account a password yet. Then, set the password for root. Disable anonymous access, disable remote login via root, and remove the test database. This is a production machine, and we have control over our root account - we can do <i>anything</i>; we do not need these things designed for a development machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>MongoDB</h1>\r\n<p>I use MongoDB for my projects, so I\'ll include this here. MongoDB is <i>also</i> very easy to setup:\r\n<pre>pacman -Ss mongodb</pre>\r\nThis will probably install a bunch (maybe four) things alongside mongodb - it\'s all good! Remember to start it:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/mongodb start</pre>\r\n</p>','Databases','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-7','','','2011-04-21 07:08:25','2011-04-21 07:08:25','',126,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/140/126-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(141,1,'2011-04-19 07:01:12','2011-04-19 07:01:12','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\r\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. So... let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>OnLoad</h1>\r\n<p>When we login, we\'ll need to initialise RVM, with the following line placed in one of our <a href=\"appendix-a-startup-files\">startup files</a>:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nMake sure you\'ve read the appendix on startup-files! You\'ll probably want to place the line in <tt>.bashsrc</tt>, and source <tt>.bashrc</tt> from <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, like most configurations. <i>Remember</i>: We need to place the line in both <tt>/root/</tt> and <tt>/etc/skel/</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby - indeed, they will compile the vast majority of packages we install. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-38','','','2011-04-19 07:01:12','2011-04-19 07:01:12','',54,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/141/54-revision-38',0,'revision','',0),(142,1,'2011-04-11 14:15:49','2011-04-11 14:15:49','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivial - but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you too don\'t feel horrendously useless. If, in reality, you <i>are</i> horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So come along, my homies, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Yo, here be ground rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i> (that is, a collection of technologies that will comprise our server). The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul><li>Archlinux</li><li>RVM</li><li>nginx</li><li>Passenger</li><li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li><li>Rails</li></ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, private.</p>\r\n\r\n','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-13','','','2011-04-11 14:15:49','2011-04-11 14:15:49','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/142/22-revision-13',0,'revision','',0),(143,1,'2011-04-29 07:18:52','2011-04-29 07:18:52','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivial - but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you too don\'t feel horrendously useless. If, in reality, you actually *are* horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So walk beside me on this mystical journey, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Ground Rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i>. The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Archlinux</li>\r\n  <li>RVM</li>\r\n  <li>nginx</li>\r\n  <li>Passenger</li>\r\n  <li>fast-cgi</li>\r\n  <li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li>\r\n  <li>Rails</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, soldier.</p>\r\n\r\n','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-14','','','2011-04-29 07:18:52','2011-04-29 07:18:52','',22,'http://localhost/wordpress/posts/143/22-revision-14',0,'revision','',0),(144,1,'2011-04-19 07:01:29','2011-04-19 07:01:29','<p class=\"overview\">\"To serve one\'s country - that is the dream. That, and occasionally a very naughty nurse\" - Voltaire</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Problem with nginx</h1>\r\n<p>Hush now, it\'s great. We all love it. However, unlike Apache it doesn\'t support loadable modules. That means for every extension/module we wish to use with nginx, we\'ll need to recompile nginx. What a pain! Fortunately for us, Archlinux makes this easy for us - we won\'t even be doing any manual compiling. Instead, we\'ll be downloading and using a package that is set up to compile nginx with passenger support. To do this, we\'ll need to access the AUR.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The AUR</h1>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_User_Repository\">Archlinux User Repository</a> is a community-driven repository for Arch users. It contains packages that we can\'t access through Pacman. The AUR is <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/\">primarily accessed through the web</a>. You can search for packages, download them, build them, and then use Pacman to install them. We\'re going to do that for the package <a href=\"https://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=28185\"><tt>nginx-passenger</tt></a>. You\'ll notice there are a few different links to tarballs and a PKGBUILD file. We\'ll be downloading the tarball (I threw this in a directory I made at <tt>~/AUR</tt>):\r\n<pre>wget aur.archlinx.org/packages/nginx-passenger/nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ntar -xvf nginx-passenger.tar.gz\r\ncd nginx-passenger\r\n</pre>\r\nNow we\'re in the directory (well, <i>I\'m</i> in the directory) <tt>~/AUR/nginx-passenger</tt>. In this directory, we can build the package.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>makepkg</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nLet\'s just do it:\r\n<pre>makepkg --asroot -s</pre>\r\n<tt>--asroot</tt> allows us to run the command as root. <tt>makepkg</tt> would throw an error otherwise - sometimes doing things as root is unsafe. This time, it\'s fine. <tt>-s</tt> tells makepkg to look at the listed dependencies and automagically install them. There shouldn\'t be many, if any. This command may take some time to execute, as it is compiling and stuff. When it\'s done, we have a package that Pacman can use! Install the package like so:\r\n<pre>pacman -U nginx-passenger.pkg.tar.xs</pre>\r\nPow! You now have an Archlinux-targeted version of nginx, with passenger support, installed on your system! Give yourself a high-five!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Running the damn thing</h1>\r\n<p>There is a single good reason why we went through the trouble of getting our package through the AUR, rather than the (admittedly easier) Passeneger install script. The Passenger install script isn\'t targeted for Archlinux - it\'s for Linuxes in general. That means it wouldn\'t have several useful features, such as a control script. How useful is a control script? Let\'s try running nginx to find out:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx start</pre>\r\nBam. Easy. You can also <tt>stop</tt> it, <tt>restart</tt> it (stops and starts it), and <tt>reload</tt> it (just reparses the configuration files without restarting - very useful). </p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Final Configuration (important)</h1>\r\n<p>We\'re not finished just yet. We will need to tell nginx where to find the Passenger executables and what-not. nginx\'s configuration is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. It\'s a file - open it with whatever text-editor you like (this author sheepishly admits to using nano, having never used a terminal for any significant editing). You\'ll see a whole bunch of stuff in there. Go take a look, look at the nginx documentation if you want to know what some of it does, we\'ll definitely be coming back to it later. We\'re going to add two lines. One will tell nginx where Passenger has its <i>things</i>, the other line will tell nginx where to find a ruby executable for Passenger to use.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s figure out where our passenger root is:\r\n<pre>passenger-config --root</pre>\r\nBam! <tt>passenger-config</tt> should display a path to where Passenger is installed to. Remember this! We shall call it <tt>output #1</tt>. We\'re also going to need to know where our ruby is:\r\n<pre>which ruby</pre>\r\nHooray! We shall call this <tt>output #2</tt>. Now we have the information we need to configure nginx. Look at the following:\r\n<pre>passenger_root [output #1]\r\npassenger_ruby [output #2]</pre>\r\nDon\'t include those square brackets. Mine looks like this:\r\n<pre>\r\npassenger_root /usr/local/rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p180/gems/passenger-3.0.6\r\npassenger_ruby /usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby\r\n</pre>\r\nNow, finally, place those two lines into your <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt> file. Somewhere near the top - outside the <tt>html</tt> block (some would say the <i>top-level</i>). Awesome. Quick! Reload the nginx configuration:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</pre>\r\nAnd breathe.\r\n<h1>Summary</h1>\r\nYou now have nginx with Passenger up and running. You still don\'t have Rails installed, and you have nothing to point your webserver to. We will rectify this shortly.','nginx & Passenger','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-17','','','2011-04-19 07:01:29','2011-04-19 07:01:29','',48,'http://localhost/posts/144/48-revision-17',0,'revision','',0),(145,1,'2011-05-02 08:30:03','2011-05-02 08:30:03','<p class=\"overview\">\"PHP, once exulted on high, is now scorned with such vigour that many consider Lisp a via alternative\" - Benjamin Franklin</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>PHP still drives the web. And many, <i>many</i> blogs use Wordpress, including this one. Therefore, we\'d like to have PHP support alongside Ruby support. And it\'s easy! So we\'ll do it!</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>php-fpm</h1>\r\n<p>FastCGI is a technology that allows nginx to interact with many external tools, such as PHP. php-fpm is a FastCGI process spawner. It comes in the latest versions of PHP (5.3.3 and higher). And that\'s great news, because previous methods for installation were annoying. To install php-fpm, it couldn\'t be easier:\r\n<pre>pacman -S php-fpm</pre>\r\nIf you haven\'t already installed PHP proper, it\'ll want to do that too, as it\'s a dependency. Then, you\'ll need to start it:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/php-fpm start</pre>\r\nGreat! Now you\'ve got PHP and a FastCGI process-spawner ready to go. We just need to configure nginx to run PHP when a PHP-file is requested.\r\n</p>','PHP','','publish','open','open','','php','','','2011-05-06 06:30:09','2011-05-06 06:30:09','',22,'http://localhost/?page_id=145',3,'page','',0),(146,1,'2011-05-02 08:30:01','2011-05-02 08:30:01','<p class=\"overview\">\"PHP, once exulted on high, is now scorned with such vigour that many consider Lisp a via alternative\" - Benjamin Franklin</p>\n\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\n<p>PHP still drives the web. And many, <i>many</i> blogs use Wordpress, including this one. Therefore, we\'d like to have PHP support alongside Ruby support. And it\'s easy! So we\'ll do it!</p>\n\n<h1>php-fpm</h1>\n<p>FastCGI is a technology that allows nginx to interact with many external tools, such as PHP. php-fpm is a FastCGI process spawner. It comes in the latest versions of PHP (5.3.3 and higher). And that\'s great news, because previous methods for installation were annoying. To install php-fpm, it couldn\'t be easier:\n<pre>pacman -S php-fpm</pre>\nIf you haven\'t already installed PHP proper, it\'ll want to do that too, as it\'s a dependency. Then, you\'ll need to start it:\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/php-fpm start</pre>\nGreat! Now you\'ve got FastCGI processes ready to go. We just need to point nginx at them. This will allow us to handle php files.\n</p>\n\n<h1>nginx Configuration</h1>\n<p>','PHP','','inherit','open','open','','145-revision','','','2011-05-02 08:30:01','2011-05-02 08:30:01','',145,'http://localhost/posts/146/145-revision',0,'revision','',0),(147,1,'2011-05-02 08:35:56','2011-05-02 08:35:56','<p class=\"overview\">\"PHP, once exulted on high, is now scorned with such vigour that many consider Lisp a via alternative\" - Benjamin Franklin</p>\n\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\n<p>PHP still drives the web. And many, <i>many</i> blogs use Wordpress, including this one. Therefore, we\'d like to have PHP support alongside Ruby support. And it\'s easy! So we\'ll do it!</p>\n\n<h1>php-fpm</h1>\n<p>FastCGI is a technology that allows nginx to interact with many external tools, such as PHP. php-fpm is a FastCGI process spawner. It comes in the latest versions of PHP (5.3.3 and higher). And that\'s great news, because previous methods for installation were annoying. To install php-fpm, it couldn\'t be easier:\n<pre>pacman -S php-fpm</pre>\nIf you haven\'t already installed PHP proper, it\'ll want to do that too, as it\'s a dependency. Then, you\'ll need to start it:\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/php-fpm start</pre>\nGreat! Now you\'ve got PHP and a FastCGI process-spawner ready to go. We just need to point nginx at them. This will allow us to handle php files.\n</p>\n\n<h1>nginx Configuration</h1>\n<p>\nWe\'re going to edit <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. Firstly, we need to tell nginx that \"index.php\" is an index file. Find and edit this part of the file to look like this (we\'ve simply added \"index.php\" onto the end):\n<pre>location / {\n      root    html;\n      index   index.html index.htm index.php;\n}</pre>\n\nSecondly, we need to configure the php-handler part of nginx. Uncomment these lines and edit the file to be as follows:\n<pre>location ~ \\.php$ {\n      root           html;\n      fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\n      fastcgi_index  index.php; \n      fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  /srv/http/nginx/$fastcgi_script_name;\n      include        fastcgi_params;\n}</pre>\n</p>','PHP','','inherit','open','open','','145-autosave','','','2011-05-02 08:35:56','2011-05-02 08:35:56','',145,'http://localhost/posts/147/145-autosave',0,'revision','',0),(148,1,'2011-05-02 08:30:03','2011-05-02 08:30:03','<p class=\"overview\">\"PHP, once exulted on high, is now scorned with such vigour that many consider Lisp a via alternative\" - Benjamin Franklin</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>PHP still drives the web. And many, <i>many</i> blogs use Wordpress, including this one. Therefore, we\'d like to have PHP support alongside Ruby support. And it\'s easy! So we\'ll do it!</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>php-fpm</h1>\r\n<p>FastCGI is a technology that allows nginx to interact with many external tools, such as PHP. php-fpm is a FastCGI process spawner. It comes in the latest versions of PHP (5.3.3 and higher). And that\'s great news, because previous methods for installation were annoying. To install php-fpm, it couldn\'t be easier:\r\n<pre>pacman -S php-fpm</pre>\r\nIf you haven\'t already installed PHP proper, it\'ll want to do that too, as it\'s a dependency. Then, you\'ll need to start it:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/php-fpm start</pre>\r\nGreat! Now you\'ve got FastCGI processes ready to go. We just need to point nginx at them. This will allow us to handle php files.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>nginx Configuration</h1>\r\n<p></p>','PHP','','inherit','open','open','','145-revision-2','','','2011-05-02 08:30:03','2011-05-02 08:30:03','',145,'http://localhost/posts/148/145-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(149,1,'2011-05-02 08:31:11','2011-05-02 08:31:11','<p class=\"overview\">\"PHP, once exulted on high, is now scorned with such vigour that many consider Lisp a via alternative\" - Benjamin Franklin</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>PHP still drives the web. And many, <i>many</i> blogs use Wordpress, including this one. Therefore, we\'d like to have PHP support alongside Ruby support. And it\'s easy! So we\'ll do it!</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>php-fpm</h1>\r\n<p>FastCGI is a technology that allows nginx to interact with many external tools, such as PHP. php-fpm is a FastCGI process spawner. It comes in the latest versions of PHP (5.3.3 and higher). And that\'s great news, because previous methods for installation were annoying. To install php-fpm, it couldn\'t be easier:\r\n<pre>pacman -S php-fpm</pre>\r\nIf you haven\'t already installed PHP proper, it\'ll want to do that too, as it\'s a dependency. Then, you\'ll need to start it:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/php-fpm start</pre>\r\nGreat! Now you\'ve got PHP and a FastCGI process-spawner ready to go. We just need to point nginx at them. This will allow us to handle php files.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>nginx Configuration</h1>\r\n<p></p>','PHP','','inherit','open','open','','145-revision-3','','','2011-05-02 08:31:11','2011-05-02 08:31:11','',145,'http://localhost/posts/149/145-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(150,1,'2011-05-02 08:33:53','2011-05-02 08:33:53','<p class=\"overview\">\"PHP, once exulted on high, is now scorned with such vigour that many consider Lisp a via alternative\" - Benjamin Franklin</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>PHP still drives the web. And many, <i>many</i> blogs use Wordpress, including this one. Therefore, we\'d like to have PHP support alongside Ruby support. And it\'s easy! So we\'ll do it!</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>php-fpm</h1>\r\n<p>FastCGI is a technology that allows nginx to interact with many external tools, such as PHP. php-fpm is a FastCGI process spawner. It comes in the latest versions of PHP (5.3.3 and higher). And that\'s great news, because previous methods for installation were annoying. To install php-fpm, it couldn\'t be easier:\r\n<pre>pacman -S php-fpm</pre>\r\nIf you haven\'t already installed PHP proper, it\'ll want to do that too, as it\'s a dependency. Then, you\'ll need to start it:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/php-fpm start</pre>\r\nGreat! Now you\'ve got PHP and a FastCGI process-spawner ready to go. We just need to point nginx at them. This will allow us to handle php files.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>nginx Configuration</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nWe\'re going to edit <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. Firstly, we need to tell nginx that \"index.php\" is an index file. Find and edit this part of the file to look like this (we\'ve simply added \"index.php\" onto the end):\r\n<pre>location / {\r\n      root    html;\r\n      index   index.html index.htm index.php;\r\n}</pre>\r\n\r\n2: Un-comment these lines and edit in the file to be as follows:\r\n location ~ \\.php$ {\r\n      root           html;\r\n      fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\r\n      fastcgi_index  index.php; \r\n      fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  /srv/http/nginx/$fastcgi_script_name;\r\n      include        fastcgi_params;\r\n\r\n</p>','PHP','','inherit','open','open','','145-revision-4','','','2011-05-02 08:33:53','2011-05-02 08:33:53','',145,'http://localhost/posts/150/145-revision-4',0,'revision','',0),(151,1,'2011-05-03 06:13:04','2011-05-03 06:13:04','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Let\'s get back to basics. The default <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file is <i>long</i>, and full of confusing things. Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser http http;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>http</tt>, in group <tt>http</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. However, in addition to these things, <tt>root</tt> also sets the <tt>$document_root</tt> variable. That will be important to us if we wish to configure PHP later on. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website. If you write <tt>index.html</tt> in <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and navigate in your browser to localhost, nginx should serve up the page! Hooray!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\r\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</pre>\r\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. Then, in its stead, place <tt>include sites-enabled/*;</tt>. We now have our two files:\r\n<table><tr><td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n\r\n  include sites-enabled/*;\r\n}\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  root /home/username/website/public;\r\n  index index.html index.htm;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Enabler</h1>\r\n<p>As you may have guessed, our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file will include all files in <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</tt>. But there is nothing there! Time for a symlink:\r\n<pre>\r\nln -s /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled/website.com\r\n</pre>\r\nNow reload your nginx configuration (<tt>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</tt>). nginx will be serving files from <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>. Hooray!\r\n','nginx Configuration','','publish','open','open','','nginx-configuration','','','2011-05-09 04:43:32','2011-05-09 04:43:32','',22,'http://localhost/?page_id=151',0,'page','',0),(152,1,'2011-05-03 05:27:37','2011-05-03 05:27:37','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\n\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision','','','2011-05-03 05:27:37','2011-05-03 05:27:37','',151,'http://localhost/posts/152/151-revision',0,'revision','',0),(153,1,'2011-05-05 10:21:11','2011-05-05 10:21:11','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\n\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\n\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\n<pre>\nuser nginx nginx;\n\nworker_processes  1;\n\nevents {\n  worker_connections 1024;\n}\n\nhttp {\n  include mime.types;\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\n}\n</pre>\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>nginx</tt>, in group <tt>nginx</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\n</p>\n\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\n<p>\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\n<pre>\nhttp {\n  ...\n\n  server {\n    listen 80;\n    root /home/username/website/public;\n    index index.html index.htm;\n  }\n}\n</pre>\n\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website. If you write <tt>index.html</tt> in <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and navigate in your browser to 127.0.0.1, nginx should serve up the page! Hooray!\n</p>\n\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</pre>\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. Then, in its stead, place <tt>include sites-enabled/*;</tt>. We now have our two files:\n<table><tr><td>\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\n<pre>\nuser nginx nginx;\n\nworker_processes  1;\n\nevents {\n  worker_connections 1024;\n}\n\nhttp {\n  include mime.types;\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\n\n  include sites-enabled/*;\n}\n\n</pre>\n</td>\n<td>\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</tt>\n<pre>\nserver {\n  listen 80;\n  root /home/username/website/public;\n  index index.html index.htm;\n}\n</pre>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n</p>\n\n<h1>The Enabler</h1>\n<p>As you may have guessed, our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file will include all files in <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</tt>. But there is nothing there! Time for a symlink:\n<pre>\nln -s /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled/website.com\n</pre>\nNow reload your nginx configuration (<tt>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</tt>). nginx will be serving files from <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>. Hooray!\n','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-autosave','','','2011-05-05 10:21:11','2011-05-05 10:21:11','',151,'http://localhost/posts/153/151-autosave',0,'revision','',0),(154,1,'2011-05-03 06:13:04','2011-05-03 06:13:04','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-2','','','2011-05-03 06:13:04','2011-05-03 06:13:04','',151,'http://localhost/posts/154/151-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(155,1,'2011-05-03 06:17:30','2011-05-03 06:17:30','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-3','','','2011-05-03 06:17:30','2011-05-03 06:17:30','',151,'http://localhost/posts/155/151-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(156,1,'2011-05-03 06:19:45','2011-05-03 06:19:45','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\n# user and group to run as\r\nuser  ez ez;\r\n# number of nginx workers\r\nworker_processes  6;\r\n# pid of nginx master process\r\npid /var/run/nginx.pid;\r\n# Number of worker connections. 1024 is a good default\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-4','','','2011-05-03 06:19:45','2011-05-03 06:19:45','',151,'http://localhost/posts/156/151-revision-4',0,'revision','',0),(157,1,'2011-05-03 06:23:36','2011-05-03 06:23:36','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understandin