nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying. It should be noted that this is all we need to serve static files. \r\n\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-13','','','2011-05-04 03:35:17','2011-05-04 03:35:17','',151,'http://localhost/posts/165/151-revision-13',0,'revision','',0),(166,1,'2011-05-05 06:44:12','2011-05-05 06:44:12','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>nginx</tt>, in group <tt>nginx</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website.\r\n\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-14','','','2011-05-05 06:44:12','2011-05-05 06:44:12','',151,'http://localhost/posts/166/151-revision-14',0,'revision','',0),(167,1,'2011-05-05 06:51:37','2011-05-05 06:51:37','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>nginx</tt>, in group <tt>nginx</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background.\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-15','','','2011-05-05 06:51:37','2011-05-05 06:51:37','',151,'http://localhost/posts/167/151-revision-15',0,'revision','',0),(168,1,'2011-05-05 06:57:34','2011-05-05 06:57:34','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>nginx</tt>, in group <tt>nginx</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\r\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/test.com</pre>\r\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. We now have our two files:\r\n<table><tr><td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n\r\n  include sites-enabled/*;\r\n}\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  root /home/username/website/public;\r\n  index index.html index.htm;\r\n}\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-16','','','2011-05-05 06:57:34','2011-05-05 06:57:34','',151,'http://localhost/posts/168/151-revision-16',0,'revision','',0),(169,1,'2011-05-05 06:58:05','2011-05-05 06:58:05','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre