ot /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\r\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</pre>\r\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. We now have our two files:\r\n<table><tr><td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n\r\n  include sites-enabled/*;\r\n}\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  root /home/username/website/public;\r\n  index index.html index.htm;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-18','','','2011-05-05 06:58:46','2011-05-05 06:58:46','',151,'http://localhost/posts/170/151-revision-18',0,'revision','',0),(171,1,'2011-05-05 07:00:02','2011-05-05 07:00:02','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>nginx</tt>, in group <tt>nginx</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\r\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</pre>\r\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. We now have our two files:\r\n<table><tr><td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\n  http {\r\n    include mime.types;\r\n    default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n\r\n    include sites-enabled/*;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  root /home/username/website/public;\r\n  index index.html index.htm;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-19','','','2011-05-05 07:00:02','2011-05-05 07:00:02','',151,'http://localhost/posts/171/151-revision-19',0,'revision','',0),(172,1,'2011-05-05 07:07:07','2011-05-05 07:07:07','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>nginx</tt>, in group <tt>nginx</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\r\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</pre>\r\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. We now have our two files:\r\n<table><tr><td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n\r\n  include sites-enabled/*;\r\n}\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  root /home/username/website/public;\r\n  index index.html index.htm;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-20','','','2011-05-05 07:07:07','2011-05-05 07:07:07','',151,'http://localhost/posts/172/151-revision-20',0,'revision','',0),(173,1,'2011-05-05 07:08:14','2011-05-05 07:08:14','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>nginx</tt>, in group <tt>nginx</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\r\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</pre>\r\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. Then, in its stead, place <tt>include sites-enabled/*;</tt>. We now have our two files:\r\n<table><tr><td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n\r\n  include sites-enabled/*;\r\n}\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  root /home/username/website/public;\r\n  index index.html index.htm;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-21','','','2011-05-05 07:08:14','2011-05-05 07:08:14','',151,'http://localhost/posts/173/151-revision-21',0,'revision','',0),(174,1,'2011-05-05 07:14:07','2011-05-05 07:14:07','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>nginx</tt>, in group <tt>nginx</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\r\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</pre>\r\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. Then, in its stead, place <tt>include sites-enabled/*;</tt>. We now have our two files:\r\n<table><tr><td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n\r\n  include sites-enabled/*;\r\n}\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  root /home/username/website/public;\r\n  index index.html index.htm;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Enabler</h1>\r\n<p>As you may have guessed, our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file will include all files in <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</tt>. But there is nothing there! Time for a symlink:\r\n<pre>\r\nln -s /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled/website.com\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h1>Managing Multiple Sites</h1>\r\n<p>Using one server for multiple websites is the practical man\'s option - especially if you have little traffic. Let\'s have a brief glance at a very bare-bones version of ','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-22','','','2011-05-05 07:14:07','2011-05-05 07:14:07','',151,'http://localhost/posts/174/151-revision-22',0,'revision','',0),(175,1,'2011-05-06 03:37:46','2011-05-06 03:37:46','<p class=\"overview\">\"Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" - Arthur C. Clarke</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>PHP</h1>\r\n<p>To serve PHP files, nginx needs to know two things. It needs to know where to send the command, as it is not nginx that executes PHP scripts, but PHP itself. It also needs to know which files it\'s referring to. Let\'s take a look:\r\n<pre>\r\nlocation ~ \\.php$ {\r\n  fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\r\n  fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nFirst things first: Our regex tells us to match any files that end with <tt>.php</tt>. That\'s the easy part.</p>\r\n<p>\r\nNow. We are passing our PHP scripts to <tt>php-fpm</tt>. <tt>php-fpm</tt>, when running, has a network socket in the filesystem that we can connect to, rather than specifying a local server somewhere; this is what <tt>fastcgi_pass</tt> specifies. <tt>fastcgi_param</tt> has a bunch of options. The <tt>SCRIPT_FILENAME</tt> option tells <tt>nginx</tt> how to construct the filename to pass along to <tt>php-fpm</tt>. In our example, <tt>$document_root</tt> is set to whatever <tt>root</tt> specifies, further up in our file (mine is <tt>/home/username/testsite</tt>). <tt>$fastcgi_script_name</tt> is automagically set to the requested url-file. So if the url was <tt>jona.cc/index.php</tt>, <tt>$document_root$fastcgi_script_name</tt> would equate to <tt>/home/username/testsite/index.php</tt>. And that\'s the script that <tt>php-fpm</tt> would execute.</p>','Advanced nginx Configuration','','publish','open','open','','advanced-nginx-configuration','','','2011-05-09 04:56:48','2011-05-09 04:56:48','',0,'http://localhost/?page_id=175',0,'page','',0),(176,1,'2011-05-06 03:37:19','2011-05-06 03:37:19','<p class=\"overview\">\"Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" - Arthur C. Clarke</p>\n\n<h1>PHP</h1>\n<p>To serve PHP files, nginx needs to know two things. It needs to know where to send the command, as it is not nginx that executes PHP scripts, but PHP itself. It also needs to know how \n<pre>\nlocation ~ \\.php$ {\n  fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\n  fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\n</pre>\n','Advanced nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision','','','2011-05-06 03:37:19','2011-05-06 03:37:19','',175,'http://localhost/posts/176/175-revision',0,'revision','',0),(177,1,'2011-05-06 06:25:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2011-05-06 06:25:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://localhost/?p=177',0,'post','',0),(178,1,'2011-04-29 07:20:04','2011-04-29 07:20:04','<p class=\"overview\">This article is for all of you for whom coding a site is trivia, but for whom configuring a production server is a new or confusing experience. I tried and failed (and eventually succeeded) over the course of a week, so here\'s a guide so you, too, don\'t feel horrendously useless. If in reality you actually *are* horrendously useless, I can not guarantee this article will make you suddenly useful. This will be step-by-step-ish, but also contain general, broad advice for unix administration. So walk beside me on this mystical journey, as I explain some stuff that I should have learnt/remembered in university. I did Computer Science, for crying out loud.</p>\r\n<h1>Ground Rules</h1>\r\n<p>This article is going to assume a certain <i>stack</i>. The end goal will be a machine that can serve a website, as that\'s what most of us hackers are building - websites, or \"web applications\", which are pretentious websites. Here\'s the stack:\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Archlinux</li>\r\n  <li>RVM</li>\r\n  <li>nginx</li>\r\n  <li>Passenger</li>\r\n  <li>fast-cgi</li>\r\n  <li>A handful of commonly-used databases</li>\r\n  <li>Rails</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nYes, some of those are trivial, but for the sake of completeness, there they are. Can\'t say I didn\'t warn you, soldier.</p>\r\n\r\n','Basic Server Management (for hackers)','','inherit','open','open','','22-revision-15','','','2011-04-29 07:20:04','2011-04-29 07:20:04','',22,'http://localhost/posts/178/22-revision-15',0,'revision','',0),(179,1,'2011-04-29 07:09:12','2011-04-29 07:09:12','<p class=\"overview\">\"For RVM said \'thou shall not fight amongst thyselves, as wouldst geese\', and there was much joy, and offended geese\"<br /> - Scriptures</p>\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/\">RVM</a> - I\'m not going to rationalise this for you. It is important to have RVM on your production machine to manage different versions of Ruby side-by-side (such as porting your website to a new version!). Well damn, guess I just rationalised. RVM is basically a bunch of bash scripts. Keep in mind that Archlinux has no system ruby installed. I\'ll repeat that: Archlinux does <i>not</i> come with a \"system ruby\". Okay? Okay. High five.</p>\r\n<h1>System-Wide</h1>\r\n<p>We shall be installing RVM system wide, because this is a production machine. So... let\'s do this! First, we must install some prerequisites:\r\n<pre>pacman -S curl git</pre>\r\n<tt>curl</tt> so we can actually get RVM, and <tt>git</tt>, if we wish to get the latest and greatest development version (plus, you\'re a hacker - of course you want git!).\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Now, we\'ll get and install RVM:\r\n<pre>bash < <(curl -B http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/install/rvm)</pre>\r\nThis will download and run a shell script that will automagically install RVM system-wide. However, we\'re not done.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>OnLoad</h1>\r\n<p>When we login, we\'ll need to initialise RVM, with the following line placed in one of our <a href=\"appendix-a-startup-files\">startup files</a>:\r\n<pre>[[ -s \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\" ]] && . \"/usr/local/rvm/scripts/rvm\"</pre>\r\nMake sure you\'ve read the appendix on startup-files! You\'ll probably want to place the line in <tt>.bashsrc</tt>, and source <tt>.bashrc</tt> from <tt>.bash_profile</tt>, like most configurations. <i>Remember</i>: We need to place the line in both <tt>/root/</tt> and <tt>/etc/skel/</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, after installing RVM, we need to write \"the line\" to <tt>/etc/skel/.bash_profile</tt>. Then, copy-paste that file to <tt>~/.bash_profile</tt>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>RVM: Installing a Ruby</h1>\r\n<p>First, let\'s install some prerequisites:</p>\r\n<pre>pacman -S base-devel</pre>\r\n<tt>base-devel</tt> is basically just a grouping of certain packages (gcc, make, etc). These packages are required for compiling Ruby - indeed, they will compile the vast majority of packages we install. RVM will do all the work for us, but it still needs the tools present. After those packages are installed, we can finally install our first Ruby:\r\n<pre>rvm install 1.9.2</pre>\r\nYou do not need to choose version 1.9.2, but this guide will. RVM is great because if we ever wish to support an app that relies on 1.8.7 behaviour, or something from Ree, we can install that version and set up some hooks to change versions magically. That\'s RVM\'s beauty. The compilation will take some time. After the installation is complete, you have one (1) working version of Ruby. However, your <tt>PATH</tt> doesn\'t contain the path the ruby yet. We need to tell RVM to do that:\r\n<pre>rvm --default 1.9.2</pre>\r\nWe\'ve just told RVM to use the 1.9.2 ruby. It will have set up our <tt>PATH</tt> to point to it, so if you <tt>which ruby</tt>, you should get something like <tt>/usr/local/rvm/rubies/ruby-1.9.2-p180/bin/ruby</tt>. The <tt>--default</tt> flag tells RVM to use 1.9.2 as the default Ruby. This means that on login, when RVM loads, it will automatically set <tt>PATH</tt> towards 1.9.2. Handy, no?','RVM & Ruby','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-39','','','2011-04-29 07:09:12','2011-04-29 07:09:12','',54,'http://localhost/posts/179/54-revision-39',0,'revision','',0),(180,1,'2011-05-02 08:36:01','2011-05-02 08:36:01','<p class=\"overview\">\"PHP, once exulted on high, is now scorned with such vigour that many consider Lisp a via alternative\" - Benjamin Franklin</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Rationale</h1>\r\n<p>PHP still drives the web. And many, <i>many</i> blogs use Wordpress, including this one. Therefore, we\'d like to have PHP support alongside Ruby support. And it\'s easy! So we\'ll do it!</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>php-fpm</h1>\r\n<p>FastCGI is a technology that allows nginx to interact with many external tools, such as PHP. php-fpm is a FastCGI process spawner. It comes in the latest versions of PHP (5.3.3 and higher). And that\'s great news, because previous methods for installation were annoying. To install php-fpm, it couldn\'t be easier:\r\n<pre>pacman -S php-fpm</pre>\r\nIf you haven\'t already installed PHP proper, it\'ll want to do that too, as it\'s a dependency. Then, you\'ll need to start it:\r\n<pre>/etc/rc.d/php-fpm start</pre>\r\nGreat! Now you\'ve got PHP and a FastCGI process-spawner ready to go. We just need to point nginx at them. This will allow us to handle php files.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>nginx Configuration</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nWe\'re going to edit <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. Firstly, we need to tell nginx that \"index.php\" is an index file. Find and edit this part of the file to look like this (we\'ve simply added \"index.php\" onto the end):\r\n<pre>location / {\r\n      root    html;\r\n      index   index.html index.htm index.php;\r\n}</pre>\r\n\r\nSecondly, we need to configure the php-handler part of nginx. Uncomment these lines and edit the file to be as follows:\r\n<pre>location ~ \\.php$ {\r\n      root           html;\r\n      fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\r\n      fastcgi_index  index.php; \r\n      fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  /srv/http/nginx/$fastcgi_script_name;\r\n      include        fastcgi_params;\r\n}</pre>\r\n</p>','PHP','','inherit','open','open','','145-revision-5','','','2011-05-02 08:36:01','2011-05-02 08:36:01','',145,'http://localhost/posts/180/145-revision-5',0,'revision','',0),(181,1,'2011-05-05 14:34:02','2011-05-05 14:34:02','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>nginx</tt>, in group <tt>nginx</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website. If you write <tt>index.html</tt> in <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and navigate in your browser to 127.0.0.1, nginx should serve up the page! Hooray!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\r\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</pre>\r\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. Then, in its stead, place <tt>include sites-enabled/*;</tt>. We now have our two files:\r\n<table><tr><td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n\r\n  include sites-enabled/*;\r\n}\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  root /home/username/website/public;\r\n  index index.html index.htm;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Enabler</h1>\r\n<p>As you may have guessed, our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file will include all files in <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</tt>. But there is nothing there! Time for a symlink:\r\n<pre>\r\nln -s /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled/website.com\r\n</pre>\r\nNow reload your nginx configuration (<tt>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</tt>). nginx will be serving files from <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>. Hooray!\r\n','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-23','','','2011-05-05 14:34:02','2011-05-05 14:34:02','',151,'http://localhost/posts/181/151-revision-23',0,'revision','',0),(182,1,'2011-05-09 04:54:45','2011-05-09 04:54:45','<p class=\"overview\">\"Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" - Arthur C. Clarke</p>\n\n<h1>PHP</h1>\n<p>To serve PHP files, nginx needs to know two things. It needs to know where to send the command, as it is not nginx that executes PHP scripts, but PHP itself. It also needs to know how \n<pre>\nlocation ~ \\.php$ {\n  fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\n  fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\n}\n</pre>\nWe are passing our PGP scripts to <tt>php-fpm</tt>. <tt>php-fpm</tt>, when running, has a network socket in the filesystem that we can connect to, rather than specifying a local server somewhere; this is what <tt>fastcgi_pass</tt> specifies. <tt>fastcgi_param</tt> has a bunch of options. The <tt>SCRIPT_FILENAME</tt> option tells <tt>nginx</tt> how to construct the filename to pass along to <tt>php-fpm</tt>. In our example, <tt>$document_root</tt> is set to whatever <tt>root</tt> specifies, further up in our file (mine is <tt>/home/username/testsite</tt>). <tt>$fastcgi_script_name</tt> is automagically set to the requested url-file. So if the url was <tt>jona.cc/index.php</tt>, <tt>$document_root$fastcgi_script_name</tt> would equate to <tt>/home/username/testsite/index.php</tt>. And t','Advanced nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','175-autosave','','','2011-05-09 04:54:45','2011-05-09 04:54:45','',175,'http://localhost/posts/182/175-autosave',0,'revision','',0),(183,1,'2011-05-06 06:31:56','2011-05-06 06:31:56','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Let\'s get back to basics. The default <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file is <i>long</i>, and full of confusing things. Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>nginx</tt>, in group <tt>nginx</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website. If you write <tt>index.html</tt> in <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and navigate in your browser to 127.0.0.1, nginx should serve up the page! Hooray!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\r\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</pre>\r\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. Then, in its stead, place <tt>include sites-enabled/*;</tt>. We now have our two files:\r\n<table><tr><td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n\r\n  include sites-enabled/*;\r\n}\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  root /home/username/website/public;\r\n  index index.html index.htm;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Enabler</h1>\r\n<p>As you may have guessed, our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file will include all files in <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</tt>. But there is nothing there! Time for a symlink:\r\n<pre>\r\nln -s /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled/website.com\r\n</pre>\r\nNow reload your nginx configuration (<tt>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</tt>). nginx will be serving files from <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>. Hooray!\r\n','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-24','','','2011-05-06 06:31:56','2011-05-06 06:31:56','',151,'http://localhost/posts/183/151-revision-24',0,'revision','',0),(184,1,'2011-05-06 03:37:46','2011-05-06 03:37:46','<p class=\"overview\">\"Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" - Arthur C. Clarke</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>PHP</h1>\r\n<p>To serve PHP files, nginx needs to know two things. It needs to know where to send the command, as it is not nginx that executes PHP scripts, but PHP itself. It also needs to know how \r\n<pre>\r\nlocation ~ \\.php$ {\r\n  fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\r\n  fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\r\n</pre>\r\n','Advanced nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision-2','','','2011-05-06 03:37:46','2011-05-06 03:37:46','',175,'http://localhost/posts/184/175-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(185,1,'2011-05-09 04:21:18','2011-05-09 04:21:18','<p class=\"overview\">\"Don\'t you ever, get together, when you\'re far away, when you\'re far away, the nights are long, well it\'s something that you\'ve never seen, but it\'s hard to say, well it\'s hard to say\" - Wolfmother</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Why And The How</h1>\r\n<p>nginx\'s configuration is managed through a single file, the file we\'ve been editing - <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>. This file controls how nginx responds to <i>everything</i>. Soon, however, we\'ll be splitting this file up into multiple files. We can <tt>include</tt> these files from <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, allowing for a more systematic organisation of our configuration. We\'ll also be going over basic rules that will give us a good understanding of nginx; these rules will help govern conventional and normal websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Bare-bones</h1>\r\n<p>Let\'s get back to basics. The default <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file is <i>long</i>, and full of confusing things. Here is a bare-bones file for nginx:\r\n<pre>\r\nuser http http;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe <tt>user</tt> directive is important. <tt>nginx</tt> runs as a default user, but this default user can be changed during installation, so you can never be sure what it is. Instead, we will tell nginx to run all its worker-processes as user <tt>http</tt>, in group <tt>http</tt>. This is important because the file permissions of our website (in our filesystem), need to allow for execution. We\'ll cover this in more detail later.</p><p>Let\'s ignore <tt>worker_processes</tt> and <tt>worker_connections</tt> for now. Perhaps you can guess what they do. Instead, let\'s focus on the <tt>http</tt> block. You\'ll notice we\'re already including another file (which is located at <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/mime.types</tt>). We\'ve also specified a default type, just in nginx can\'t figure it out for itself. As it stands, our nginx will do absolutely nothing useful. It can\'t serve anything, because we haven\'t told it to.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Adding a Server</h1>\r\n<p>\r\nInside the <tt>http</tt> block, we need to place a <tt>server</tt> block. This will represent one website (we call these \"virtual hosts\").\r\n<pre>\r\nhttp {\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  server {\r\n    listen 80;\r\n    root /home/username/website/public;\r\n    index index.html index.htm;\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAnalysis is easy. We are listening on port 80, the root of our website is located at (a made up) path <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and <i>index files</i> are <tt>index.html</tt> or <tt>index.htm</tt>. I\'m going to assume you understand those three things. If you don\'t, go forth and learn. It should be noted that at this point, our webserver is capable of displaying our basic, static-files-only website. If you write <tt>index.html</tt> in <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>, and navigate in your browser to 127.0.0.1, nginx should serve up the page! Hooray!\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Location, Location, Location</h1>\r\n<p>If you run multiple websites off a single server, you will want to manage the separate sites independently. Since all configuration (that we\'re interested in) in nginx is done through <tt>nginx.conf</tt>, all websites would have to be listed and configured inside this single file. That can get... overwhelming. Instead, we\'ll break out our servers into multiple files. Let us create two directories:\r\n<pre>mkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available\r\nmkdir /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</pre>\r\nThis should be familiar to people from an Apache background. We will now make a website in <tt>sites-available</tt>:\r\n<pre>vi /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</pre>\r\nCut-and-paste the <tt>server</tt> block portion of our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file into this file. Then, in its stead, place <tt>include sites-enabled/*;</tt>. We now have our two files:\r\n<table><tr><td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/nginx.conf</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nuser nginx nginx;\r\n\r\nworker_processes  1;\r\n\r\nevents {\r\n  worker_connections 1024;\r\n}\r\n\r\nhttp {\r\n  include mime.types;\r\n  default_type application/octet-stream;\r\n\r\n  include sites-enabled/*;\r\n}\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com</tt>\r\n<pre>\r\nserver {\r\n  listen 80;\r\n  root /home/username/website/public;\r\n  index index.html index.htm;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>The Enabler</h1>\r\n<p>As you may have guessed, our <tt>nginx.conf</tt> file will include all files in <tt>/etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled</tt>. But there is nothing there! Time for a symlink:\r\n<pre>\r\nln -s /etc/nginx/conf/sites-available/website.com /etc/nginx/conf/sites-enabled/website.com\r\n</pre>\r\nNow reload your nginx configuration (<tt>/etc/rc.d/nginx reload</tt>). nginx will be serving files from <tt>/home/username/website/public</tt>. Hooray!\r\n','nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-25','','','2011-05-09 04:21:18','2011-05-09 04:21:18','',151,'http://localhost/posts/185/151-revision-25',0,'revision','',0),(186,1,'2011-05-09 04:26:21','2011-05-09 04:26:21','<p class=\"overview\">\"Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" - Arthur C. Clarke</p>\n\n<h1>PHP</h1>\n<p>To serve PHP files, nginx needs to know two things. It needs to know where to send the command, as it is not nginx that executes PHP scripts, but PHP itself. It also needs to know how \n<pre>\nlocation ~ \\.php$ {\n  fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\n  fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\n}\n</pre>\n','Advanced nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision-3','','','2011-05-09 04:26:21','2011-05-09 04:26:21','',175,'http://localhost/posts/186/175-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(187,1,'2011-05-09 04:44:08','2011-05-09 04:44:08','<p class=\"overview\">\"Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" - Arthur C. Clarke</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>PHP</h1>\r\n<p>To serve PHP files, nginx needs to know two things. It needs to know where to send the command, as it is not nginx that executes PHP scripts, but PHP itself. It also needs to know how \r\n<pre>\r\nlocation ~ \\.php$ {\r\n  fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\r\n  fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nWe should note that <tt>$document_root</tt> must be set correctly, which it will be if you set the <tt>root</tt> directive correctly.','Advanced nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision-4','','','2011-05-09 04:44:08','2011-05-09 04:44:08','',175,'http://localhost/posts/187/175-revision-4',0,'revision','',0),(188,1,'2011-05-09 04:44:42','2011-05-09 04:44:42','<p class=\"overview\">\"Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" - Arthur C. Clarke</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>PHP</h1>\r\n<p>To serve PHP files, nginx needs to know two things. It needs to know where to send the command, as it is not nginx that executes PHP scripts, but PHP itself. It also needs to know how \r\n<pre>\r\nlocation ~ \\.php$ {\r\n  fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\r\n  fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nNote that <tt>$document_root</tt> must be set, which it will be if you set the <tt>root</tt> directive correctly (in the <tt>server</tt> block).','Advanced nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision-5','','','2011-05-09 04:44:42','2011-05-09 04:44:42','',175,'http://localhost/posts/188/175-revision-5',0,'revision','',0),(189,1,'2011-05-09 04:54:56','2011-05-09 04:54:56','<p class=\"overview\">\"Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" - Arthur C. Clarke</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>PHP</h1>\r\n<p>To serve PHP files, nginx needs to know two things. It needs to know where to send the command, as it is not nginx that executes PHP scripts, but PHP itself. It also needs to know how \r\n<pre>\r\nlocation ~ \\.php$ {\r\n  fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\r\n  fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nWe are passing our PGP scripts to <tt>php-fpm</tt>. <tt>php-fpm</tt>, when running, has a network socket in the filesystem that we can connect to, rather than specifying a local server somewhere; this is what <tt>fastcgi_pass</tt> specifies. <tt>fastcgi_param</tt> has a bunch of options. The <tt>SCRIPT_FILENAME</tt> option tells <tt>nginx</tt> how to construct the filename to pass along to <tt>php-fpm</tt>. In our example, <tt>$document_root</tt> is set to whatever <tt>root</tt> specifies, further up in our file (mine is <tt>/home/username/testsite</tt>). <tt>$fastcgi_script_name</tt> is automagically set to the requested url-file. So if the url was <tt>jona.cc/index.php</tt>, <tt>$document_root$fastcgi_script_name</tt> would equate to <tt>/home/username/testsite/index.php</tt>. And that\'s the script that <tt>php-fpm</tt> would execute.','Advanced nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision-6','','','2011-05-09 04:54:56','2011-05-09 04:54:56','',175,'http://localhost/posts/189/175-revision-6',0,'revision','',0),(190,1,'2011-05-09 04:55:40','2011-05-09 04:55:40','<p class=\"overview\">\"Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" - Arthur C. Clarke</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>PHP</h1>\r\n<p>To serve PHP files, nginx needs to know two things. It needs to know where to send the command, as it is not nginx that executes PHP scripts, but PHP itself. It also needs to know which files it\'s referring to. Let\'s take a look:\r\n<pre>\r\nlocation ~ \\.php$ {\r\n  fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\r\n  fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nWe are passing our PGP scripts to <tt>php-fpm</tt>. <tt>php-fpm</tt>, when running, has a network socket in the filesystem that we can connect to, rather than specifying a local server somewhere; this is what <tt>fastcgi_pass</tt> specifies. <tt>fastcgi_param</tt> has a bunch of options. The <tt>SCRIPT_FILENAME</tt> option tells <tt>nginx</tt> how to construct the filename to pass along to <tt>php-fpm</tt>. In our example, <tt>$document_root</tt> is set to whatever <tt>root</tt> specifies, further up in our file (mine is <tt>/home/username/testsite</tt>). <tt>$fastcgi_script_name</tt> is automagically set to the requested url-file. So if the url was <tt>jona.cc/index.php</tt>, <tt>$document_root$fastcgi_script_name</tt> would equate to <tt>/home/username/testsite/index.php</tt>. And that\'s the script that <tt>php-fpm</tt> would execute.','Advanced nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision-7','','','2011-05-09 04:55:40','2011-05-09 04:55:40','',175,'http://localhost/posts/190/175-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(191,1,'2011-05-09 04:56:30','2011-05-09 04:56:30','<p class=\"overview\">\"Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" - Arthur C. Clarke</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>PHP</h1>\r\n<p>To serve PHP files, nginx needs to know two things. It needs to know where to send the command, as it is not nginx that executes PHP scripts, but PHP itself. It also needs to know which files it\'s referring to. Let\'s take a look:\r\n<pre>\r\nlocation ~ \\.php$ {\r\n  fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;\r\n  fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME  $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nFirst things first: Our regex tells us to match any files that end with <tt>.php</tt>. That\'s the easy part.</p>\r\n<p>\r\nNow. We are passing our PGP scripts to <tt>php-fpm</tt>. <tt>php-fpm</tt>, when running, has a network socket in the filesystem that we can connect to, rather than specifying a local server somewhere; this is what <tt>fastcgi_pass</tt> specifies. <tt>fastcgi_param</tt> has a bunch of options. The <tt>SCRIPT_FILENAME</tt> option tells <tt>nginx</tt> how to construct the filename to pass along to <tt>php-fpm</tt>. In our example, <tt>$document_root</tt> is set to whatever <tt>root</tt> specifies, further up in our file (mine is <tt>/home/username/testsite</tt>). <tt>$fastcgi_script_name</tt> is automagically set to the requested url-file. So if the url was <tt>jona.cc/index.php</tt>, <tt>$document_root$fastcgi_script_name</tt> would equate to <tt>/home/username/testsite/index.php</tt>. And that\'s the script that <tt>php-fpm</tt> would execute.</p>','Advanced nginx Configuration','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision-8','','','2011-05-09 04:56:30','2011-05-09 04:56:30','',175,'http://localhost/posts/191/175-revision-8',0,'revision','',0);
